# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: citizen-science
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] In the 1980s, 3D printing techniques were considered suitable only for the production of functional or aesthetic prototypes, and a more appropriate term for it at the time was rapid prototyping.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] As of 2019, the precision, repeatability, and material range of 3D printing have increased to the point that some 3D printing processes are considered viable as an industrial-production technology; in this context, the term *additive manufacturing* can be used synonymously with *3D printing*.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] One of the key advantages of 3D printing is the ability to produce very complex shapes or geometries that would be otherwise infeasible to construct by hand, including hollow parts or parts with internal truss structures to reduce weight while creating less material waste.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Fused deposition modeling (FDM), which uses a continuous filament of a thermoplastic material, is the most common 3D printing process in use as of 2020.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] The umbrella term *additive manufacturing (AM)* gained popularity in the 2000s, inspired by the theme of material being added together (in any of various ways).
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] In contrast, the term *subtractive manufacturing* appeared as a retronym for the large family of machining processes with material *removal* as their common process.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] The term *3D printing* still referred only to the polymer technologies in most minds, and the term *AM* was more likely to be used in metalworking and end-use part production contexts than among polymer, inkjet, or stereolithography enthusiasts.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Until recently, the term *3D printing* has been associated with machines low in price or capability.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] *3D printing* and *additive manufacturing* reflect that the technologies share the theme of material addition or joining throughout a 3D work envelope under automated control.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Other terms that have been used as synonyms or hypernyms have included *desktop manufacturing*, *rapid manufacturing* (as the logical production-level successor to *rapid prototyping*), and *on-demand manufacturing* (which echoes *on-demand printing* in the 2D sense of *printing*).
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Today, the term *subtractive* has not replaced the term *machining*, instead complementing it when a term that covers any removal method is needed.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Agile tooling is the use of modular means to design tooling that is produced by additive manufacturing or 3D printing methods to enable quick prototyping and responses to tooling and fixture needs.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Agile tooling uses a cost-effective and high-quality method to quickly respond to customer and market needs, and it can be used in hydroforming, stamping, injection molding and other manufacturing processes.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Although the terms 3D printing and additive manufacturing can both be seen as the same thing, some standards organizitons make a distinction between them.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] The American National Standards Institute (ANSI) says that international standards such as IS0/ASTM 52900 define additive manufacturing as the process of building parts from 3D model data and adding material layer by layer.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] In comparison, 3D printing is described as creating objects by depositing material through a print head or some variation of a nozzle type of device.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] In industrial and technical settings, additive manufacturing is often the preferred term, and 3D printing is used more by the general public.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] The general concept of and procedure to be used in 3D-printing was first described by Murray Leinster in his 1945 short story "Things Pass By": "But this constructor is both efficient and flexible.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] I feed magnetronic plastics — the stuff they make houses and ships of nowadays — into this moving arm.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] It makes drawings in the air following drawings it scans with photo-cells.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Jones in his story, "Tools of the Trade", published in the November 1950 issue of *Astounding Science Fiction* magazine.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] He referred to it as a "molecular spray" in that story.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] On 27 July 1971, Johannes F Gottwald received U.S. patent 3596285A for the "Liquid Metal Recorder", after applying on 11 July 1969 a continuous inkjet metal material device to form a removable metal fabrication on a reusable surface for immediate use or salvaged for printing again by remelting.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] This appears to be the first patent describing 3D printing with rapid prototyping and controlled on-demand manufacturing of patterns.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Jones laid out the concept of 3D printing in his regular column *Ariadne* in the journal *New Scientist*.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Early additive manufacturing equipment and materials were developed in the 1980s.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] In April 1980, Hideo Kodama of Nagoya Municipal Industrial Research Institute invented two additive methods for fabricating three-dimensional plastic models with photo-hardening thermoset polymer, where the UV exposure area is controlled by a mask pattern or a scanning fiber transmitter.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] He filed a patent for this XYZ plotter, which was published on 10 November 1981.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] His research results as journal papers were published in April and November 1981.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] However, there was no reaction to the series of his publications.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] His device was not highly evaluated in the laboratory and his boss did not show any interest.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] His research budget was just 60,000 yen or $545 a year.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Acquiring the patent rights for the XYZ plotter was abandoned, and the project was terminated.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] On 2 July 1984, American entrepreneur Bill Masters filed a patent for his computer automated manufacturing process and system (US 4665492).
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] This filing is on record at the USPTO as the first 3D printing patent in history; it was the first of three patents belonging to Masters that laid the foundation for the 3D printing systems used today.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] On 16 July 1984, Alain Le Méhauté, Olivier de Witte, and Jean Claude André filed their patent for the stereolithography process.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] The application of the French inventors was abandoned by the French General Electric Company (now Alcatel-Alsthom) and CILAS (The Laser Consortium).
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] The claimed reason was "for lack of business perspective".
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Research (later named Howtek, Inc. in February 1984) to develop Pixelmaster, a color inkjet 2D printer using Thermoplastic (hot-melt) plastic ink, which was commercialized in 1986.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] A team was put together, 6 members from Exxon Office Systems, Danbury Systems Division, an inkjet printer startup and some members of Howtek, Inc group who became popular figures in the 3D printing industry.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] One Howtek member was Richard Helinski, responsible for patent US5136515A ("Method and Means for constructing three-dimensional articles by particle deposition", application 7 November 1989 granted 4 August 1992).
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] He formed C.A.D-Cast, Inc (later renamed to Visual Impact Corporation (VIC) on 22 August 1991), a New Hampshire company.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] The company's prototype VIC 3D printer is available with a video presentation showing a 3D model printed with a single nozzle inkjet.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Another employee, Herbert Menhennett, formed HM Research, a New Hampshire company, in 1991 and introduced the Howtek, Inc, inkjet technology and thermoplastic materials to Royden Sanders of SDI and Bill Masters of Ballistic Particle Manufacturing (BPM), where he worked for a number of years.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Both BPM 3D printers and SPI 3D printers use Howtek, Inc style Inkjets and materials.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] McMahon, who was hired by Howtek, Inc to help develop the inkjet, later worked at Sanders Prototype and now operates Layer Grown Model Technology, a 3D service provider specializing in Howtek single nozzle inkjet and SDI printer support.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] McMahon worked with Steven Zoltan, inventor of the 1972 drop-on-demand inkjet at Exxon and holder of a 1978 patent that expanded the understanding of the single nozzle design inkjets (Alpha jets), to help perfect the Howtek, Inc hot-melt inkjets.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] This Howtek hot-melt thermoplastic technology is popular with metal investment casting, especially in the 3D printing jewelry industry.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Royden Sanders licensed the Helinksi patent prior to manufacturing the Modelmaker 6 Pro at Sanders prototype, Inc (SPI) in 1993.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] The first customer of the Modelmaker 6Pro was Hitchner Corporations, Metal Casting Technology, Inc in Milford, New Hampshire, a mile from the SDI facility in late 1993–1995 casting golf clubs and auto engine parts.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Hull defined the process as a "system for generating three-dimensional objects by creating a cross-sectional pattern of the object to be formed".
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Hull's contribution was the STL (Stereolithography) file format and the digital slicing and infill strategies common to many processes today.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] In 1986, Charles "Chuck" Hull was granted a patent for this system, and his company, 3D Systems Corporation was formed and it released the first commercial 3D printer, the SLA-1, later in 1987 or 1988.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] The technology used by most 3D printers to date—especially hobbyist and consumer-oriented models—is fused deposition modeling, a special application of plastic extrusion, developed in 1988 by S.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Scott Crump and commercialized by his company Stratasys, which marketed its first FDM machine in 1992.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] AM processes for metal sintering or melting (such as selective laser sintering, direct metal laser sintering, and selective laser melting) usually went by their own individual names in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] However, the automated techniques that *added* metal, which would later be called additive manufacturing, were beginning to challenge that assumption.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] By the mid-1990s, new techniques for material deposition were developed at Stanford and Carnegie Mellon University, including microcasting and sprayed materials.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Sacrificial and support materials had also become more common, enabling new object geometries.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] The term *3D printing* originally referred to a powder bed process employing standard and custom inkjet print heads, developed at MIT by Emanuel Sachs in 1993 and commercialized by Soligen Technologies, Extrude Hone Corporation, and Z Corporation.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] The year 1993 also saw the start of an inkjet 3D printer company initially named Sanders Prototype, Inc and later named Solidscape, introducing a high-precision polymer jet fabrication system with soluble support structures, (categorized as a "dot-on-dot" technique).
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] In 1995 the Fraunhofer Society developed the selective laser melting process.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] In the early 2000s 3D printers were still largely being used just in the manufacturing and research industries, as the technology was still relatively young and was too expensive for most consumers to be able to get their hands on.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] The 2000s was when larger scale use of the technology began being seen in industry, most often in the architecture and medical industries, though it was typically used for low accuracy modeling and testing, rather than the production of common manufactured goods or heavy prototyping.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] In 2005 users began to design and distribute plans for 3D printers that could print around 70% of their own parts, the original plans of which were designed by Adrian Bowyer at the University of Bath in 2004, with the name of the project being RepRap (Replicating Rapid-prototyper).
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Similarly, in 2006 the Fab@Home project was started by Evan Malone and Hod Lipson, another project whose purpose was to design a low-cost and open source fabrication system that users could develop on their own and post feedback on, making the project very collaborative.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Much of the software for 3D printing available to the public at the time was open source, and as such was quickly distributed and improved upon by many individual users.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] In 2009 the Fused Deposition Modeling (FDM) printing process patents expired.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] This opened the door to a new wave of startup companies, many of which were established by major contributors of these open source initiatives, with the goal of many of them being to start developing commercial FDM 3D printers that were more accessible to the general public.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] As the various additive processes matured, it became clear that soon metal removal would no longer be the only metalworking process done through a tool or head moving through a 3D work envelope, transforming a mass of raw material into a desired shape layer by layer.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] The 2010s were the first decade in which metal end-use parts such as engine brackets and large nuts would be grown (either before or instead of machining) in job production rather than obligately being machined from bar stock or plate.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] One place that AM is making a significant inroad is in the aviation industry.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] With nearly 3.8 billion air travelers in 2016, the demand for fuel efficient and easily produced jet engines has never been higher.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] One example of AM integration with aerospace was in 2016 when Airbus delivered the first of GE's LEAP engines.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] This engine has integrated 3D-printed fuel nozzles, reducing parts from 20 to 1, a 25% weight reduction, and reduced assembly times.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] A fuel nozzle is the perfect inroad for additive manufacturing in a jet engine since it allows for optimized design of the complex internals and it is a low-stress, non-rotating part.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Similarly, in 2015, PW delivered their first AM parts in the PurePower PW1500G to Bombardier.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Sticking to low-stress, non-rotating parts, PW selected the compressor stators and synch ring brackets to roll out this new manufacturing technology for the first time.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] While AM is still playing a small role in the total number of parts in the jet engine manufacturing process, the return on investment can already be seen by the reduction in parts, the rapid production capabilities and the "optimized design in terms of performance and cost".
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] As technology matured, several authors began to speculate that 3D printing could aid in sustainable development in the developing world.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] In 2012, Filabot developed a system for closing the loop with plastic and allows for any FDM or FFF 3D printer to be able to print with a wider range of plastics.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Tentzeris demonstrated the first multi-material, vertically integrated printed electronics additive manufacturing platform (VIPRE) which enabled 3D printing of functional electronics operating up to 40 GHz.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] As the price of printers started to drop people interested in this technology had more access and freedom to make what they wanted.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] As of 2014, the price for commercial printers was still high with the cost being over $2,000.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] The term "3D printing" originally referred to a process that deposits a binder material onto a powder bed with inkjet printer heads layer by layer.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] More recently, the popular vernacular has started using the term to encompass a wider variety of additive-manufacturing techniques such as electron-beam additive manufacturing and selective laser melting.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] The United States and global technical standards use the official term *additive manufacturing* for this broader sense.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] The most commonly used 3D printing process (46% as of 2018) is a material extrusion technique called fused deposition modeling, or FDM.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] While FDM technology was invented after the other two most popular technologies, stereolithography (SLA) and selective laser sintering (SLS), FDM is typically the most inexpensive of the three by a large margin, which lends to the popularity of the process.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] As of 2020, 3D printers have reached the level of quality and price that allows most people to enter the world of 3D printing.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] In 2020 decent quality printers can be found for less than US$200 for entry-level machines.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] These more affordable printers are usually fused deposition modeling (FDM) printers.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] In November 2021 a British patient named Steve Verze received the world's first fully 3D-printed prosthetic eye from the Moorfields Eye Hospital in London.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] In April 2024, the world's largest 3D printer, the Factory of the Future 1.0 was revealed at the University of Maine.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] It is able to make objects 96 feet long, or 29 meters.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] In 2024, researchers used machine learning to improve the construction of synthetic bone and set a record for shock absorption.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] In July 2024, researchers published a paper in *Advanced Materials Technologies* describing the development of artificial blood vessels using 3D-printing technology, which are as strong and durable as natural blood vessels.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] The process involved using a rotating spindle integrated into a 3D printer to create grafts from a water-based gel, which were then coated in biodegradable polyester molecules.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] In October 2025, the North Bristol NHS Trust reported that a UK cyclist named Dave Richards had received a full-face 3D-printed prosthesis, created at the newly opened Bristol 3D Medical Center at North Bristol NHS Trust.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Led by senior reconstructive scientist Amy Davey, the process used advanced scanning and medical-grade resins to replicate his facial features after severe burns.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] It marked a milestone in integrated medical 3D-printing facilities in the UK.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Additive manufacturing or 3D printing has rapidly gained importance in the field of engineering due to its many benefits.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] The vision of 3D printing is design freedom, individualization, decentralization and executing processes that were previously impossible through alternative methods.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Some of these benefits include enabling faster prototyping, reducing manufacturing costs, increasing product customization, and improving product quality.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Furthermore, the capabilities of 3D printing have extended beyond traditional manufacturing, like lightweight construction, or repair and maintenance with applications in prosthetics, bioprinting, food industry, rocket building, design and art and renewable energy systems.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] 3D printing technology can be used to produce battery energy storage systems, which are essential for sustainable energy generation and distribution.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Another benefit of 3D printing is the technology's ability to produce complex geometries with high precision and accuracy.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] This is particularly relevant in the field of microwave engineering, where 3D printing can be used to produce components with unique properties that are difficult to achieve using traditional manufacturing methods.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Additive Manufacturing processes generate minimal waste by adding material only where needed, unlike traditional methods that cut away excess material.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] This reduces both material costs and environmental impact.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] This reduction in waste also lowers energy consumption for material production and disposal, contributing to a smaller carbon footprint.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] 3D printable models may be created with a computer-aided design (CAD) package, via a 3D scanner, or by a plain digital camera and photogrammetry software.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] 3D printed models created with CAD result in relatively fewer errors than other methods.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Errors in 3D printable models can be identified and corrected before printing.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] The manual modeling process of preparing geometric data for 3D computer graphics is similar to plastic arts such as sculpting.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] 3D scanning is a process of collecting digital data on the shape and appearance of a real object, and creating a digital model based on it.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] CAD models can be saved in the stereolithography file format (STL), a de facto CAD file format for additive manufacturing that stores data based on triangulations of the surface of CAD models.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] STL is not tailored for additive manufacturing because it generates large file sizes of topology-optimized parts and lattice structures due to the large number of surfaces involved.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] A newer CAD file format, the additive manufacturing file format (AMF), was introduced in 2011 to solve this problem.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] It stores information using curved triangulations.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Before printing a 3D model from an STL file, it must first be examined for errors.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] A step in the STL generation known as "repair" fixes such problems in the original model.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Generally, STLs that have been produced from a model obtained through 3D scanning often have more of these errors as 3D scanning is often achieved by point to point acquisition/mapping.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] 3D reconstruction often includes errors.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Once completed, the STL file needs to be processed by a piece of software called a "slicer", which converts the model into a series of thin layers and produces a G-code file containing instructions tailored to a specific type of 3D printer.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] For instance FDM printers use FDM file formats.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] This G-code file can then be printed with 3D printing client software (which loads the G-code and uses it to instruct the 3D printer during the 3D printing process).
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Printer resolution describes layer thickness and X–Y resolution in dots per inch (dpi) or micrometers (μm).
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Typical layer thickness is around 100 μm (250 DPI), although some machines can print layers as thin as 16 μm (1,600 DPI).
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] X–Y resolution is comparable to that of laser printers.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] For that printer resolution, specifying a mesh resolution of 0.01–0.03 mm and a chord length ≤ 0.016 mm generates an optimal STL output file for a given model input file.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Specifying higher resolution results in larger files without increase in print quality.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Construction of a model with contemporary methods can take anywhere from several hours to several days, depending on the method used and the size and complexity of the model.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Additive systems can typically reduce this time to a few hours, although it varies widely depending on the type of machine used and the size and number of models being produced simultaneously.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Though the printer-produced resolution and surface finish are sufficient for some applications, post-processing and finishing methods allow for benefits such as greater dimensional accuracy, smoother surfaces, and other modifications such as coloration.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] The surface finish of a 3D-printed part can improved using subtractive methods such as sanding and bead blasting.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] When smoothing parts that require dimensional accuracy, it is important to take into account the volume of the material being removed.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Some printable polymers, such as acrylonitrile butadiene styrene (ABS), allow the surface finish to be smoothed and improved using chemical vapor processes based on acetone or similar solvents.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Some additive manufacturing techniques can benefit from annealing as a post-processing step.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Annealing a 3D-printed part allows for better internal layer bonding due to recrystallization of the part.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] It allows for an increase in mechanical properties, some of which are fracture toughness, flexural strength, impact resistance, and heat resistance.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Annealing a component may not be suitable for applications where dimensional accuracy is required, as it can introduce warpage or shrinkage due to heating and cooling.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Some additively manufactured parts—especially parts that are mission critical—are post-processed with hot isostatic pressing to improve the density and to configure the microstructure to get the required mechanical performance of the printed parts.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Additive or subtractive hybrid manufacturing (ASHM) is a method that involves producing a 3D printed part and using machining (subtractive manufacturing) to remove material.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Machining operations can be completed after each layer, or after the entire 3D print has been completed depending on the application requirements.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] These hybrid methods allow for 3D-printed parts to achieve better surface finishes and dimensional accuracy.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] The layered structure of traditional additive manufacturing processes leads to a stair-stepping effect on part-surfaces that are curved or tilted with respect to the building platform.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] The effect strongly depends on the layer height used, as well as the orientation of a part surface inside the building process.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] This effect can be minimized using "variable layer heights" or "adaptive layer heights".
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] These methods decrease the layer height in places where higher quality is needed.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Painting a 3D-printed part offers a range of finishes and appearances that may not be achievable through most 3D printing techniques.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] The process typically involves several steps, such as surface preparation, priming, and painting.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] These steps help prepare the surface of the part and ensuring the paint adheres properly.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Some additive manufacturing techniques are capable of using multiple materials simultaneously.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] These techniques are able to print in multiple colors and color combinations simultaneously and can produce parts that may not necessarily require painting.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Some printing techniques require internal supports to be built to support overhanging features during construction.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] These supports must be mechanically removed or dissolved if using a water-soluble support material such as PVA after completing a print.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Some commercial metal 3D printers involve cutting the metal component off the metal substrate after deposition.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] A new process for the GMAW 3D printing allows for substrate surface modifications to remove aluminium or steel.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Traditionally, 3D printing focused on polymers for printing, due to the ease of manufacturing and handling polymeric materials.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] However, the method has rapidly evolved to not only print various polymers but also metals, chocolates, and ceramics, making 3D printing a versatile option for manufacturing.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Layer-by-layer fabrication of three-dimensional physical models is a modern concept that "stems from the ever-growing CAD industry, more specifically the solid modeling side of CAD.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Before solid modeling was introduced in the late 1980s, three-dimensional models were created with wire frames and surfaces." but in all cases the layers of materials are controlled by the printer and the material properties.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] The three-dimensional material layer is controlled by the deposition rate as set by the printer operator and stored in a computer file.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] The earliest printed patented material was a hot melt type ink for printing patterns using a heated metal alloy.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Charles Hull filed the first patent on August 8, 1984, to use a UV-cured acrylic resin using a UV-masked light source at UVP Corp to build a simple model.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] The SLA-1 was the first SL product announced by 3D Systems at Autofact Exposition, Detroit, November 1978.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] The SLA-1 Beta shipped in Jan 1988 to Baxter Healthcare, Pratt and Whitney, General Motors and AMP.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] The first production SLA-1 shipped to Precision Castparts in April 1988.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] The UV resin material changed over quickly to an epoxy-based material resin.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] In both cases, SLA-1 models needed UV oven curing after being rinsed in a solvent cleaner to remove uncured boundary resin.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] A post cure apparatus (PCA) was sold with all systems.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] The early resin printers required a blade to move fresh resin over the model on each layer.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] The layer thickness was 0.006 inches and the HeCd laser model of the SLA-1 was 12 watts and swept across the surface at 30 inch per second.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] UVP was acquired by 3D Systems in January 1990.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] A review of the history shows that a number of materials (resins, plastic powder, plastic filament and hot-melt plastic ink) were used in the 1980s for patents in the rapid prototyping field.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Masked lamp UV-cured resin was also introduced by Cubital's Itzchak Pomerantz in the Soldier 5600, Carl Deckard's (DTM) laser sintered thermoplastic powders, and adhesive-laser cut paper (LOM) stacked to form objects by Michael Feygin before 3D Systems made its first announcement.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] The most common polymers for personal 3D printers are polylactic acid (PLA) and PETG.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Efforts to achieve multi-material 3D printing range from enhanced FDM-like processes like VoxelJet to novel voxel-based printing technologies like layered assembly.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] A drawback of many existing 3D printing technologies is that they only allow one material to be printed at a time, limiting many potential applications that require the integration of different materials in the same object.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Multi-material 3D printing solves this problem by allowing objects of complex and heterogeneous arrangements of materials to be manufactured using a single printer.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Here, a material must be specified for each voxel (or 3D printing pixel element) inside the final object volume.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] The process can be fraught with complications, however, due to the isolated and monolithic algorithms.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Some commercial devices have sought to solve these issues, such as building a Spec2Fab translator, but the progress is still very limited.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Nonetheless, in the medical industry, a concept of 3D-printed pills and vaccines has been presented.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] With this new concept, multiple medications can be combined, which is expected to decrease many risks.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] With more and more applications of multi-material 3D printing, the costs of daily life and high technology development will become inevitably lower.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Metallographic materials of 3D printing is also being researched.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] By classifying each material, CIMP-3D can systematically perform 3D printing with multiple materials.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Using 3D printing and multi-material structures in additive manufacturing has allowed for the design and creation of what is called 4D printing.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] 4D printing is an additive manufacturing process in which the printed object changes shape with time, temperature, or some other type of stimulation.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] 4D printing allows for the creation of dynamic structures with adjustable shapes, properties or functionality.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] The smart/stimulus-responsive materials that are created using 4D printing can be activated to create calculated responses such as self-assembly, self-repair, multi-functionality, reconfiguration and shape-shifting.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] This allows for customized printing of shape-changing and shape-memory materials.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] 4D printing has the potential to find new applications and uses for materials (plastics, composites, metals, etc.) and has the potential to create new alloys and composites that were not viable before.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] The versatility of this technology and materials can lead to advances in multiple fields of industry, including space, commercial and medical fields.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] The repeatability, precision, and material range for 4D printing must increase to allow the process to become more practical throughout these industries.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] To become a viable industrial production option, there are a few challenges that 4D printing must overcome.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] The challenges of 4D printing include the fact that the microstructures of these printed smart materials must be close to or better than the parts obtained through traditional machining processes.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] New and customizable materials need to be developed that have the ability to consistently respond to varying external stimuli and change to their desired shape.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] There is also a need to design new software for the various technique types of 4D printing.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] The 4D printing software will need to take into consideration the base smart material, printing technique, and structural and geometric requirements of the design.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] A variety of processes, equipment, and materials are used in the production of a three-dimensional object via additive manufacturing.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p01] Techniques include jetting, extrusion, additive friction stir deposition, powder bed fusion, binder jetting, stereolithography, computed axial lithography, liquid alternative, lamination, directed energy deposition, selective powder deposition, and cryogenic manufacturing.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing or additive manufacturing has been used in manufacturing, medical, industry and sociocultural sectors (e.g. cultural heritage) to create successful commercial technology.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] More recently, 3D printing has also been used in the humanitarian and development sector to produce a range of medical items, prosthetics, spares and repairs.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] The earliest application of additive manufacturing was on the toolroom end of the manufacturing spectrum.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] For example, rapid prototyping was one of the earliest additive variants, and its mission was to reduce the lead time and cost of developing prototypes of new parts and devices, which was earlier only done with subtractive toolroom methods such as CNC milling, turning, and precision grinding.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] In the 2010s, additive manufacturing entered production to a much greater extent.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Additive manufacturing of food is being developed by squeezing out food, layer by layer, into three-dimensional objects.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] A large variety of foods are appropriate candidates, such as chocolate and candy, and flat foods such as crackers, pasta, and pizza.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] NASA is looking into the technology in order to create 3D-printed food to limit food waste and to make food that is designed to fit an astronaut's dietary needs.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] In 2018, Italian bioengineer Giuseppe Scionti developed a technology allowing the production of fibrous plant-based meat analogues using a custom 3D bioprinter, mimicking meat texture and nutritional values.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing has entered the world of clothing, with fashion designers experimenting with 3D-printed bikinis, shoes, and dresses.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] In commercial production, Nike used 3D printing to prototype and manufacture the 2012 Vapor Laser Talon football shoe for players of American football, and New Balance has 3D manufactured custom-fit shoes for athletes.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing has come to the point where companies are printing consumer-grade eyewear with on-demand custom fit and styling (although they cannot print the lenses).
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] On-demand customization of glasses is possible with rapid prototyping.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Armor-design strategies can be enhanced by taking inspiration from nature and prototyping those designs using AM.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] In cars, trucks, and aircraft, additive manufacturing is beginning to transform both unibody and fuselage design and production, and powertrain design and production.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] For example, General Electric uses high-end 3D printers to build parts for turbines.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Many of these systems are used for rapid prototyping before mass production methods are employed.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] AM's impact on firearms involves two dimensions: new manufacturing methods for established companies, and new possibilities for the making of do-it-yourself firearms.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] In 2012, the US-based group Defense Distributed disclosed plans to design a working plastic 3D-printed firearm "that could be downloaded and reproduced by anybody with a 3D printer".
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] After Defense Distributed released their plans, questions were raised regarding the effects that 3D printing and widespread consumer-level CNC machining may have on gun control effectiveness.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Surgical uses of 3D printing-centric therapies began in the mid-1990s with anatomical modeling for bony reconstructive surgery planning.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Patient-matched implants were a natural extension of this work, leading to truly personalized implants that fit one unique individual.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Virtual planning of surgery and guidance using 3D printed, personalized instruments have been applied to many areas of surgery including total joint replacement and craniomaxillofacial reconstruction with great success.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] One example of this is the bioresorbable trachial splint to treat newborns with tracheobronchomalacia developed at the University of Michigan.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] The use of additive manufacturing for serialized production of orthopedic implants (metals) is also increasing due to the ability to efficiently create porous surface structures that facilitate osseointegration.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] The hearing aid and dental industries are expected to be the biggest areas of future development using custom 3D printing technology.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing is not just limited to inorganic materials; there have been a number of biomedical advancements made possible by 3D printing.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] As of 2012, 3D bio-printing technology has been studied by biotechnology firms and academia for possible use in tissue engineering applications in which organs and body parts are built using inkjet printing techniques.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] In this process, layers of living cells are deposited onto a gel medium or sugar matrix and slowly built up to form three-dimensional structures including vascular systems.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing has been considered as a method of implanting stem cells capable of generating new tissues and organs in living humans.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] In 2018, 3D printing technology was used for the first time to create a matrix for cell immobilization in fermentation.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Propionic acid production by *Propionibacterium acidipropionici* immobilized on 3D-printed nylon beads was chosen as a model study.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] It was shown that those 3D-printed beads were capable of promoting high-density cell attachment and propionic acid production, which could be adapted to other fermentation bioprocesses.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing has also been employed by researchers in the pharmaceutical field.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] During the last few years, there has been a surge in academic interest regarding drug delivery with the aid of AM techniques.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] This technology offers a unique way for materials to be utilized in novel formulations.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] AM manufacturing allows for the usage of materials and compounds in the development of formulations, in ways that are not possible with conventional/traditional techniques in the pharmaceutical field, e.g. tableting, cast-molding, etc.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Moreover, one of the major advantages of 3D printing, especially in the case of fused deposition modelling (FDM), is the personalization of the dosage form that can be achieved, thus, targeting the patient's specific needs.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] In the not-so-distant future, 3D printers are expected to reach hospitals and pharmacies in order to provide on-demand production of personalized formulations according to the patients' needs.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing has also been used for medical equipment.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] During the COVID-19 pandemic 3D printers were used to supplement the strained supply of PPE through volunteers using their personally owned printers to produce various pieces of personal protective equipment (i.e. frames for face shields).
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing, and open source 3D printers, in particular, are the latest technologies making inroads into the classroom.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Higher education has proven to be a major buyer of desktop and professional 3D printers which industry experts generally view as a positive indicator.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Some authors have claimed that 3D printers offer an unprecedented "revolution" in STEM education.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] The evidence for such claims comes from both the low-cost ability for rapid prototyping in the classroom by students, but also the fabrication of low-cost high-quality scientific equipment from open hardware designs forming open-source labs.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Additionally, Libraries around the world have also become locations to house smaller 3D printers for educational and community access.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Future applications for 3D printing might include creating open-source scientific equipment.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] In the 2010s, 3D printing became intensively used in the cultural heritage field for preservation, restoration and dissemination purposes.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Many Europeans and North American Museums have purchased 3D printers and actively recreate missing pieces of their relics and archaeological monuments such as Tiwanaku in Bolivia.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] The Metropolitan Museum of Art and the British Museum have started using their 3D printers to create museum souvenirs that are available in the museum shops.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Other museums, like the National Museum of Military History and Varna Historical Museum, have gone further and sell through the online platform Threeding digital models of their artifacts, created using Artec 3D scanners, in 3D printing friendly file format, which everyone can 3D print at home.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Morehshin Allahyari, an Iranian-born U.S. artist, considers her use of 3D sculpting processes of re-constructing Iranian cultural treasures as feminist activism.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Allahyari uses a 3D modeling software to reconstruct a series of cultural artifacts that were demolished by ISIS militants in 2014.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] The application of 3D printing for the representation of architectural assets has many challenges.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] In 2018, the structure of Iran National Bank was traditionally surveyed and modeled in computer graphics software (specifically, Cinema4D) and was optimized for 3D printing.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] The team tested the technique for the construction of the part and it was successful.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] After testing the procedure, the modellers reconstructed the structure in Cinema4D and exported the front part of the model to Netfabb.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] The entrance of the building was chosen due to the 3D printing limitations and the budget of the project for producing the maquette.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing was only one of the capabilities enabled by the produced 3D model of the bank, but due to the project's limited scope, the team did not continue modelling for the virtual representation or other applications.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] In 2021, Parsinejad et al. comprehensively compared the hand surveying method for 3D reconstruction ready for 3D printing with digital recording (adoption of photogrammetry method).
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] The world's first 3D-printed steel bridge was unveiled in Amsterdam in July 2021.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Spanning 12 meters over the Oudezijds Achterburgwal canal, the bridge was created using robotic arms that printed over 4,500 kilograms of stainless steel.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] 3D printed soft actuators is a growing application of 3D printing technology that has found its place in the 3D printing applications.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] These soft actuators are being developed to deal with soft structures and organs, especially in biomedical sectors and where the interaction between humans and robots is inevitable.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] The majority of the existing soft actuators are fabricated by conventional methods that require manual fabrication of devices, post-processing/assembly, and lengthy iterations until the maturity of the fabrication is achieved.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Instead of the tedious and time-consuming aspects of the current fabrication processes, researchers are exploring an appropriate manufacturing approach for the effective fabrication of soft actuators.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Thus, 3D-printed soft actuators are introduced to revolutionize the design and fabrication of soft actuators with custom geometrical, functional, and control properties in a faster and inexpensive approach.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] They also enable incorporation of all actuator components into a single structure eliminating the need to use external joints, adhesives, and fasteners.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Circuit board manufacturing involves multiple steps which include imaging, drilling, plating, solder mask coating, nomenclature printing and surface finishes.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] These steps include many chemicals such as harsh solvents and acids.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing circuit boards remove the need for many of these steps while still producing complex designs.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Polymer ink is used to create the layers of the build while silver polymer is used for creating the traces and holes used to allow electricity to flow.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Current circuit board manufacturing can be a tedious process depending on the design.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Specified materials are gathered and sent into inner layer processing where images are printed, developed and etched.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] The etch cores are typically punched to add lamination tooling.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] The cores are then prepared for lamination.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] The stack-up, the buildup of a circuit board, is built and sent into lamination where the layers are bonded.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] The boards are then measured and drilled.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Many steps may differ from this stage however for simple designs, the material goes through a plating process to plate the holes and surface.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] The outer image is then printed, developed and etched.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] After the image is defined, the material must get coated with a solder mask for later soldering.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Nomenclature is then added so components can be identified later.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] The boards are routed out of panel form into their singular or array form and then electrically tested.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Aside from the paperwork that must be completed which proves the boards meet specifications, the boards are then packed and shipped.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] The benefits of 3D printing would be that the final outline is defined from the beginning, no imaging, punching or lamination is required and electrical connections are made with the silver polymer which eliminates drilling and plating.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] The final paperwork would also be greatly reduced due to the lack of materials required to build the circuit board.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Complex designs which may take weeks to complete through normal processing can be 3D printed, greatly reducing manufacturing time.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] In 2005, academic journals began to report on the possible artistic applications of 3D printing technology.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Off-the-shelf machines were increasingly capable of producing practical household applications, for example, ornamental objects.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Some practical examples include a working clock and gears printed for home woodworking machines among other purposes.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Websites associated with home 3D printing tended to include backscratchers, coat hooks, door knobs, etc.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] As of 2017, domestic 3D printing was reaching a consumer audience beyond hobbyists and enthusiasts.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Several projects and companies are making efforts to develop affordable 3D printers for home desktop use.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Much of this work has been driven by and targeted at DIY/maker/enthusiast/early adopter communities, with additional ties to the academic and hacker communities.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Sped on by decreases in price and increases in quality, As of 2019 an estimated 2 million people worldwide have purchased a 3D printer for hobby use.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing has existed for decades within certain manufacturing industries where many legal regimes, including patents, industrial design rights, copyrights, and trademarks may apply.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] However, there is not much jurisprudence to say how these laws will apply if 3D printers become mainstream and individuals or hobbyist communities begin manufacturing items for personal use, for non-profit distribution, or for sale.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Any of the mentioned legal regimes may prohibit the distribution of the designs used in 3D printing or the distribution or sale of the printed item.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] To be allowed to do these things, where active intellectual property was involved, a person would have to contact the owner and ask for a licence, which may come with conditions and a price.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] However, many patent, design and copyright laws contain a standard limitation or exception for "private" or "non-commercial" use of inventions, designs or works of art protected under intellectual property (IP).
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] That standard limitation or exception may leave such private, non-commercial uses outside the scope of IP rights.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Patents cover inventions including processes, machines, manufacturing, and compositions of matter and have a finite duration which varies between countries, but generally 20 years from the date of application.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Therefore, if a type of wheel is patented, printing, using, or selling such a wheel could be an infringement of the patent.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Copyright covers an expression in a tangible, fixed medium and often lasts for the life of the author plus 70 years thereafter.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] For example, a sculptor retains copyright over a statue, such that other people cannot then legally distribute designs to print an identical or similar statue without paying royalties, waiting for the copyright to expire, or working within a fair use exception.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] When a feature has both artistic (copyrightable) and functional (patentable) merits when the question has appeared in US court, the courts have often held the feature is not copyrightable unless it can be separated from the functional aspects of the item.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Attempting to restrict the distribution of gun plans via the Internet has been likened to the futility of preventing the widespread distribution of DeCSS, which enabled DVD ripping.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] After the US government had Defense Distributed take down the plans, they were still widely available via the Pirate Bay and other file sharing sites.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Downloads of the plans from the UK, Germany, Spain, and Brazil were heavy.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Some US legislators have proposed regulations on 3D printers to prevent them from being used for printing guns.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing advocates have suggested that such regulations would be futile, could cripple the 3D printing industry and could infringe on free speech rights, with early pioneers of 3D printing professor Hod Lipson suggesting that gunpowder could be controlled instead.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Internationally, where gun controls are generally stricter than in the United States, some commentators have said the impact may be more strongly felt since alternative firearms are not as easily obtainable.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Officials in the United Kingdom have noted that producing a 3D-printed gun would be illegal under their gun control laws.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Europol stated that criminals have access to other sources of weapons but noted that as technology improves, the risks of an effect would increase.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] In the United States, the FAA has anticipated a desire to use additive manufacturing techniques and has been considering how best to regulate this process.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] The FAA has jurisdiction over such fabrication because all aircraft parts must be made under FAA production approval or under other FAA regulatory categories.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] In December 2016, the FAA approved the production of a 3D-printed fuel nozzle for the GE LEAP engine.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Aviation attorney Jason Dickstein has suggested that additive manufacturing is merely a production method, and should be regulated like any other production method.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] He has suggested that the FAA's focus should be on guidance to explain compliance, rather than on changing the existing rules, and that existing regulations and guidance permit a company "to develop a robust quality system that adequately reflects regulatory needs for quality assurance".
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] In 2021, first standards were issued, e.g.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] ASTM ISO/ASTM52900-21 Additive manufacturing general principles, fundamentals and vocabulary, and the above-mentioned ISO/ASTM52900-15.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] In 2023, the ISO/ASTM 52920:2023 defined the requirements for industrial additive manufacturing processes and production sites using additive manufacturing to ensure required quality level.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Aforetime in Germany there was a draft of DIN norm issued, DIN SPEC 17071:2019.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Polymer feedstock materials can release ultrafine particles and volatile organic compounds (VOCs) if sufficiently heated, which in combination have been associated with adverse respiratory and cardiovascular health effects.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] In addition, temperatures of 190 °C to 260 °C are typically reached by an FFF extrusion nozzle, which can cause skin burns.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Vat photopolymerization stereolithography printers use high-powered lasers that present a skin and eye hazard, although they are considered nonhazardous during printing because the laser is enclosed within the printing chamber.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] 3D printers also contain many moving parts that include stepper motors, pulleys, threaded rods, carriages, and small fans, which generally do not have enough power to cause serious injuries but can still trap a user's finger, long hair, or loose clothing.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Most desktop FFF 3D printers do not have any added electrical safety features beyond regular internal fuses or external transformers, although the voltages in the exposed parts of 3D printers usually do not exceed 12V to 24V, which is generally considered safe.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Research on the health and safety concerns of 3D printing is new and in development due to the recent proliferation of 3D printing devices.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] In 2017, the European Agency for Safety and Health at Work published a discussion paper on the processes and materials involved in 3D printing, the potential implications of this technology for occupational safety and health and avenues for controlling potential hazards.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Noise level is measured in decibels (dB), and can vary greatly in home printers from 15 dB to 75 dB.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Some main sources of noise in filament printers are fans, motors and bearings, while in resin printers the fans usually are responsible for most of the noise.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Some methods for dampening the noise from a printer may be to install vibration isolation, use larger diameter fans, perform regular maintenance and lubrication, or use a soundproofing enclosure.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Additive manufacturing, starting with today's infancy period, requires manufacturing firms to be flexible, ever-improving users of all available technologies to remain competitive.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Advocates of additive manufacturing also predict that this arc of technological development will counter globalization, as end users will do much of their own manufacturing rather than engage in trade to buy products from other people and corporations.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] The real integration of the newer additive technologies into commercial production, however, is more a matter of complementing traditional subtractive methods rather than displacing them entirely.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] The futurologist Jeremy Rifkin claimed that 3D printing signals the beginning of a third industrial revolution, succeeding the production line assembly that dominated manufacturing starting in the late 19th century.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Since the 1950s, a number of writers and social commentators have speculated in some depth about the social and cultural changes that might result from the advent of commercially affordable additive manufacturing technology.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] In recent years, 3D printing has created a significant impact in the humanitarian and development sector.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Its potential to facilitate distributed manufacturing is resulting in supply chain and logistics benefits, by reducing the need for transportation, warehousing and wastage.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Furthermore, social and economic development is being advanced through the creation of local production economies.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Others have suggested that as more and more 3D printers start to enter people's homes, the conventional relationship between the home and the workplace might get further eroded.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Likewise, it has also been suggested that, as it becomes easier for businesses to transmit designs for new objects around the globe, so the need for high-speed freight services might also become less.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Finally, given the ease with which certain objects can now be replicated, it remains to be seen whether changes will be made to current copyright legislation so as to protect intellectual property rights with the new technology widely available.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Some call attention to the conjunction of commons-based peer production with 3D printing and other low-cost manufacturing techniques.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] The self-reinforced fantasy of a system of eternal growth can be overcome with the development of economies of scope, and here, society can play an important role contributing to the raising of the whole productive structure to a higher plateau of more sustainable and customized productivity.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Further, it is true that many issues, problems, and threats arise due to the democratization of the means of production, and especially regarding the physical ones.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] For instance, the recyclability of advanced nanomaterials is still questioned; weapons manufacturing could become easier; not to mention the implications for counterfeiting and on intellectual property.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] It might be maintained that in contrast to the industrial paradigm whose competitive dynamics were about economies of scale, commons-based peer production 3D printing could develop economies of scope.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] While the advantages of scale rest on cheap global transportation, the economies of scope share infrastructure costs (intangible and tangible productive resources), taking advantage of the capabilities of the fabrication tools.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] And following Neil Gershenfeld in that "some of the least developed parts of the world need some of the most advanced technologies", commons-based peer production and 3D printing may offer the necessary tools for thinking globally but acting locally in response to certain needs.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Larry Summers wrote about the "devastating consequences" of 3D printing and other technologies (robots, artificial intelligence, etc.) for those who perform routine tasks.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] In his view, "already there are more American men on disability insurance than doing production work in manufacturing.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Michael Spence wrote that "Now comes a ... powerful, wave of digital technology that is replacing labor in increasingly complex tasks.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] This process of labor substitution and disintermediation has been underway for some time in service sectors—think of ATMs, online banking, enterprise resource planning, customer relationship management, mobile payment systems, and much more.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] This revolution is spreading to the production of goods, where robots and 3D printing are displacing labor." In his view, the vast majority of the cost of digital technologies comes at the start, in the design of hardware (e.g.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] 3D printers) and, more importantly, in creating the software that enables machines to carry out various tasks.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] "Once this is achieved, the marginal cost of the hardware is relatively low (and declines as scale rises), and the marginal cost of replicating the software is essentially zero.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Spence believes that, unlike prior digital technologies, which drove firms to deploy underutilized pools of valuable labor around the world, the motivating force in the current wave of digital technologies "is cost reduction via the replacement of labor".
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] For example, as the cost of 3D printing technology declines, it is "easy to imagine" that production may become "extremely" local and customized.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Moreover, production may occur in response to actual demand, not anticipated or forecast demand.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Spence believes that labor, no matter how inexpensive, will become a less important asset for growth and employment expansion, with labor-intensive, process-oriented manufacturing becoming less effective, and that re-localization will appear in both developed and developing countries.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] In his view, production will not disappear, but it will be less labor-intensive, and all countries will eventually need to rebuild their growth models around digital technologies and the human capital supporting their deployment and expansion.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Spence writes that "the world we are entering is one in which the most powerful global flows will be ideas and digital capital, not goods, services, and traditional capital.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Naomi Wu regards the usage of 3D printing in the Chinese classroom (where rote memorization is standard) to teach design principles and creativity as the most exciting recent development of the technology, and more generally regards 3D printing as being the next desktop publishing revolution.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] A printer was donated to the Juan Fernandez Women's Group in 2024, to support women in the remote community to be able to create parts to fix broken equipment, without having to wait for a ship to import the needed components.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] The growth of additive manufacturing could have a large impact on the environment.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Traditional subtractive manufacturing methods such as CNC milling create products by cutting away material from a larger block.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] In contrast, additive manufacturing creates products layer-by layer, using the minimum required materials to create the product.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] This has the benefit of reducing material waste, which further contributes to energy savings by avoiding raw material production.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Life-cycle assessment of additive manufacturing has estimated that adopting the technology could further lower carbon dioxide emissions since 3D printing creates localized production, thus reducing the need to transport products and the emissions associated.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] AM could also allow consumers to create their own replacement parts to fix purchased products to extend the lifespan of purchased products.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] By making only the bare structural necessities of products, additive manufacturing also has the potential to make profound contributions to lightweighting.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] The use of these lightweight components would allow for reductions in the energy consumption and greenhouse gas emissions of vehicles and other forms of transportation.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] A case study on an airplane component made using additive manufacturing, for example, found that the use of the component saves 63% of relevant energy and carbon dioxide emissions over the course of the product's lifetime.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] However, the adoption of additive manufacturing also has environmental disadvantages.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Firstly, AM has a high energy consumption compared to traditional processes.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] This is due to its use of processes such as lasers and high temperatures for product creation.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Secondly, despite additive manufacturing reducing up to 90% of waste compared to subtractive manufacturing, AM can generate waste that is non-recyclable.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] For example, there are issues with the recyclability of materials in metal AM as some highly regulated industries such as aerospace often insist on using virgin powder in the creation of safety critical components.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Additive manufacturing has not yet reached its theoretical material efficiency potential of 97%, but it may get closer as the technology continues to increase productivity.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Despite the drawbacks, research and industry are making further strides to support AM's sustainability.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] Some large FDM printers that melt high-density polyethylene (HDPE) pellets may also accept sufficiently clean recycled material such as chipped milk bottles.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] In addition, these printers can use shredded material from faulty builds or unsuccessful prototype versions, thus reducing overall project wastage and materials handling and storage.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] The concept has been explored in the RecycleBot.
[src:citizen-science/3d-printing-p02] There are also industrial efforts to produce metal powder from recycled metals.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The university was founded in 1928 in Aarhus, Denmark.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] It comprises five faculties - Arts, Natural Sciences, Technical Sciences, Health, and Business and Social Sciences - and a total of twenty-seven departments.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] It is home to over thirty internationally recognised research centres, including fifteen centres of excellence funded by the Danish National Research Foundation.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The university's alumni include Bjarne Stroustrup, the inventor of programming language C++; Queen Margrethe II of Denmark; King Frederik X of Denmark; and Anders Fogh Rasmussen, former prime minister of Denmark and secretary general of NATO.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Nobel Laureate Jens Christian Skou (Chemistry, 1997) conducted his groundbreaking work on the Na/K-ATPase in Aarhus and remained employed at the university until his retirement.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Two other Nobel laureates, namely Trygve Haavelmo (Economics, 1989) and Dale T.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Mortensen (Economics, 2010), were affiliated with the university.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Initially, Aarhus University was founded on 11 September 1928 as *Universitetsundervisningen i Jylland* ("University Studies in Jutland") with a budget of 33,000 DKK, and an enrollment of 64 students, which rose to 78 during the first semester.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The university was founded as a response to the increasing number of students at the University of Copenhagen after World War I.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Classrooms were rented from the Technical College and the teaching corps consisted of one professor of philosophy and four associate professors of Danish, English, German and French.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Along with the *Universitets-Samvirket* ("University Association") which consisted of representatives of Aarhus' businesses, organisations, and institutions, the municipality of Aarhus had fought since 1921 to have Denmark's next university located in the city.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] In 1929, the municipality of Aarhus gave the university land with a landscape of rolling hills.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The design of the university buildings and 12 ha campus area was assigned to architects C.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Møller, Kay Fisker and Povl Stegmann, who won the architectural competition in 1931.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Construction of the first buildings began a year later, but the campus was developed in stages and is still under development as of 2017.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Møller Architects has been responsible for the architectural design of Aarhus University in accordance with the original functionalist design key, perhaps best exemplified by the characteristic yellow brick and tile.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The first buildings were finished in 1933 and housed the Departments of Chemistry, Physics and Anatomy.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] These departments later moved to newer buildings at the campus and the original building complex now house Department of Psychology and Department of Political Science.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The construction of the first stage was funded solely by donations which totaled 935,000 Dkr and the buildings covered an area of 4,190m2.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] One of the most generous contributors to the first stage was *De Forenede Teglværker i Aarhus* ("The United Tileworks of Aarhus") led by director K.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] *Forenede Teglværker* decided to donate 1 million yellow bricks and tiles worth c.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] 50,000 Dkr and later decided to extend the donation to all bricks needed.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The inauguration on 11 September 1933, marked the first official use of the name Aarhus University and was celebrated in a tent on campus, attended by King Christian X, Queen Alexandrine, their son Crown Prince Frederik and Prime Minister Stauning together with 1000 invited guests.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] On 23 April 1934, Aarhus University was given permission to hold examinations by the king and on 10 October 1935, Professor Dr. phil.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Ernst Frandsen was appointed the first rector of the university.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Shortages of materials and a stressed economy postponed and delayed further development of Aarhus University.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] In 1941, construction of the Main Building (*Hovedbygningen*) commenced, a complex to house the university aula (assembly hall) and canteen among academic and administrative purposes.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The Main Building was finished in 1946 and still stands out from the rest of the university campus as somewhat different in its architectural design.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] In comparison with the original 4,190m2 floor space of the first buildings, Aarhus University now holds a floor space of 246,000m2 in the University Park alone.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] A series of buildings outside the main campus adds an additional floor space of 59,000m2.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] From 1928, Aarhus University offered courses in languages and philosophy, but the students were unable to finish their studies without going to the University of Copenhagen for their final examinations.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] After negotiations between the faculties in Aarhus and Copenhagen, the king declared on 8 May 1935 that the final university examinations could be held at the Faculty of Philosophy in Copenhagen as well as at the Faculty of Humanities in Aarhus.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] This was the first final examinations Aarhus University was allowed to hold, but on 24 July 1936 the king granted the Faculty of Humanities the right to hold examinations for the magister degree and in 1940 for the PhD.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Aarhus University had offered courses in basic medical subjects from 1933 and on 10 October 1935 the Faculty of Medicine was formally established.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The establishment of a Faculty of Medicine in Aarhus was met with some opposition from the Faculty of Medicine at the University of Copenhagen.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The professors thought that the state should not establish a new faculty until the shortcomings of the old one had been solved.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] In the end, the professors agreed to sign a recommendation for the new faculty as long as improvements to the old one were not delayed.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] By 1953, the Faculty of Medicine had been fully built, complete with lectures, professorship chairs, final exams, research facilities and the hospitals of Aarhus had been expanded to meet the demands of clinical training.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] In 1992, the Faculty of Medicine merged with the dental school and changed its name to Faculty of Health Sciences.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The university established its Faculty of Economics and Law in 1936, but when it offered courses in political science and in psychology (1959 and 1968, respectively), the faculty changed its name to the Faculty of Social Sciences.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The Committee approved and by declaration of the king on 5 November 1937, the faculty could hold examinations in economics and law.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Courses had been offered in theology since 1932 at the Faculty of Humanities, but in 1942 the Faculty of Theology was formally established.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Already on 22 June 1928, Reverend Balslev of Aarhus had proposed that Universitetsundervisningen i Aarhus (not yet university) taught basic courses in theology.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Though the proposal was greeted by the management, the Faculty of Theology in Copenhagen pointed out that it would take three full-time teachers of the New Testament, Old Testament and ecclesiastical history, respectively as well as education in Latin, Greek and Hebrew by the Faculty of Humanities.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] At this time, Universitetsundervisningen i Aarhus did not have the financial means to meet these criteria so the case was shelved for the time being.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] In April 1931, the case reopened, this time by Bishop Skat Hoffmeyer who proposed free teaching in the required subjects.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The management asked the faculty in Copenhagen if this was acceptable, but because the teaching was free, the faculty saw it as tutoring rather than actual teaching and they neither approved or disproved of such an approach though they did not see it as actual university teaching.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The municipality of Aarhus did not aid with funds and the management deemed a request of the state to be futile so they decided to disregard getting the teaching approved and start it anyway under the supervision of Skat Hoffmeyer.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] On 5 September 1932 the Reverend Asmund held the first lecture in theology.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] This private education in theology continued until the university could hire its own professors in 1938, and in 1942 Aarhus University could at long last establish the Faculty of Theology.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The Aarhus New University Hospital shares Masonic architectural elements related to its history of seat of the Danish Order of Freemasons.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] In 1938, the university management acknowledged it was time to consider an expansion due to lack of space and overcrowding of the auditoriums.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The solution was the Main Building (*Hovedbygningen*), containing both rooms and facilities for new academic areas, as well as housing for the general administration, an assembly hall and a canteen.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The building was to be organized according to a principle of institutes so that teaching and research took place in certain rooms with their own library and study for the professor.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The construction of the building took place during the German occupation of Denmark (1940–45) in World War II, which affected the process in more than one way.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] No state funds had been involved in the construction of the first university building and a second building for physiology, biochemistry, and a high voltage laboratory, but because the Nazis were against civil use of materials and work forces, the state contributed to the main building.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] In 1943, the Gestapo, Sicherheitsdienst, Geheime Feldpolizei and Abwehr set up their regional headquarters in the five student halls of residence on campus.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Fearing that the same would happen to the new main building, its completion was delayed.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Møller later wrote that for once there was plenty of time to work on the details of the building, like patterned brickwork, acoustic screens and furniture.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Furniture designer Aage Windeleff, designed the furniture specially for the main building, while Børge Mogensen's industrially produced furniture designs are the most commonly used elsewhere on campus.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The presence of the Gestapo in Aarhus led to multiple arrests of Danish resistance fighters and the resistance movement soon realized they needed outside assistance.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] On 31 October 1944, the Royal Air Force bombed the Gestapo's headquarters in residence halls 4 and 5, also killing ten civilian workers.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] 2 Group Bomber Command carried out the bombing by using 25 Mosquito planes.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The air strike on the University of Aarhus took place in a heavily populated area and the campus was surrounded by three hospitals.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] To avoid civilian casualties, the RAF prepared with a model of the campus, shooting at residence halls 4 and 5 with chalk bags.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Møller was in the main building during the air strike but survived and was later dug free from the rubble.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The reconstructed main building opened on 11 September 1946.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Aarhus University was an independent institution until 1970, but with management representatives from the city council and the organization of Universitets-Samvirket.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Hereafter, the university became a state-run institution under the first University Act.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] With the next University Act in 1992, external organizations were once again represented in the administration and under the 2003 Act, all Danish universities are governed by a nationwide university board.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] This board appoints the rector, deans and heads of departments instead of the students.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] It commenced in January 2004 for the first time and in August 2005, a new rector was appointed.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Earlier, in 1994, the university was a scene of a shooting; three people (including the perpetrator) were killed and two more were injured.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Aarhus University has hosted significant musical events.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The Grateful Dead played there on April 16, 1972; the recorded performance was part of the group's Europe '72 tour.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] In the 21st century, several higher education institutions have been merged with Aarhus University.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] In 2007, the National Environmental Research Institute (NERI), until then part of the Ministry of Environment and Energy, and the Danish Institute of Agricultural Sciences (DJF), until then part of the Ministry of Agriculture, were merged into AU.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The two institutions initially formed separate faculties, which later merged with the Faculty of Science to form the Faculty of Science and Technology.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] In 2012, Aarhus University's School of Engineering was merged with the university proper, making it Denmark's largest.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] A major reorganisation of the university effective 1 Jan 2011 reorganised departments into four faculties: Arts, Science and Technology, Health, and Business and Social Sciences.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] A further reorganisation occurred effective 1 Jan 2020, where Science and Technology was split into two new entities: Faculty of Technical Sciences and Faculty of Natural Sciences.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Aarhus University's main campus is located in central Aarhus, encircling the University Park (*Universitetsparken*).
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The campus master plan competition was won in 1931 by the collaborative scheme of Danish architects Kay Fisker, C.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Møller and Povl Stegmann in collaboration with landscape architect Carl Theodor Sørensen.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The design includes a wide variety of buildings in a large area, but each building is constructed of the same yellow brick and roofing tile and with a common design key, providing the whole campus with a unified appearance.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Construction commenced in 1932 and has continued into present times, lately in 1999-2001 (*Søauditorierne*) and 2014-17 (AU Health).
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The original main building was one of the first Danish functionalist public buildings and has been included in the Ministry of Culture's canon of Danish architecture; it is acknowledged as one of the twelve most significant architectural works in the cultural history of Denmark.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] In a harmonic interplay with the park, the yellow buildings form a campus that has received international recognition for its aesthetic values and it has been protected by law since 1993, in order to conserve its unique design.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Møller Architects have continued as architects of the campus ever since, except the new department of AU Health currently under construction, designed by Cubo.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The park and campus has been expanded throughout the years, in 1957 the old park of Vennelystparken, just south of the university park was included.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Apart from the main campus, Aarhus University has several smaller campuses and departments throughout Aarhus.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] This includes the campus on Fuglsangs Alle in Aarhus V, hosting a large part of Aarhus BSS, and campus Nobelparken, adjacent to the university park and built in 1997–2004 in red brick, also by C.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Archaeology and anthropology takes residence in Moesgård Manor, an old manor house at the new Moesgård Museum.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Aarhus University also has locations outside of Aarhus.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] In the city of Herning, there is a small campus where a few of the university's business, engineering and technology programmes are taught, called the Department of Business Development and Technology.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] In Copenhagen, part of the Danish School of Education is located at Campus Emdrup.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Børglum Kollegiet, and youth accommodation in Aarhus is administered by the non-profit housing cooperative of Kollegiekontoret or though the public web-platform Ungdomsboliger.dk providing access to student and youth accommodation all across Denmark.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Only the *Parkkollegierne* (full name: *Kollegierne i Universitetsparken*) dormitories are located on campus and run by Aarhus University; other dormitories are located elsewhere, all across the city.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] It is also the only dormitory exclusively for students at Aarhus University.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] As required by Danish law, the rector is appointed by the university board.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The rector in turn appoints deans and deans appoint heads of departments.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] There is no faculty senate and faculty is not involved in the appointment of rector, deans, or department heads.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Hence Danish universities has no faculty governance.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] As of 1 October 2021, more than 32,000 students were enrolled in Aarhus University.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Each year more than 1000 international exchange students come to Aarhus University to study for one or two terms.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] In 2009 close to 3000 international students were enrolled in full degree programmes.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Aarhus University is an international university with a large proportion of students at the post-baccalaureate level: over half of its students are enrolled in master's degree and PhD programmes.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] In 2011, 59 of the university's 113 Master's degree programmes were taught in English.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Talent development of young researchers has been identified as one of the university's core activities.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] This means that highly qualified students have the option of starting their PhD studies before completing their master's degree.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The university's doctoral programmes allow talented students to enroll in a combined Master's/PhD programme either right after completing the master's degree (the 5+3 track) or one year into their master's degree programme (the 4+4 track).
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Since 2006 the number of PhD students has risen from approximately 1000 to approximately 1700 in 2010.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The International Centre maintains international partnerships and combines a wide range of services for exchange students, international full-degree students, PhDs and visiting scholars.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The International Centre is often the first stop for foreign students at Aarhus University, since the centre offers advice on finding housing and living in Denmark.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Starting in 2011 all summer courses and summer schools offered by Aarhus University for bachelor's, master's and PhD students will be gathered together and expanded to provide more diversity in a new framework: AU Summer University.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] In the summer of 2011 more than 80 courses were offered within the fields of humanities, theology, social sciences, health sciences, natural sciences, agricultural sciences, business and educational sciences.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Summer courses are open to both Danish and international students.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Aarhus University has seen some deep administrational changes since the turn of the century and now also includes several large sub-departments such as Aarhus BSS, AU Engineering and others.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Each of these sub-departments offers undergraduate or graduate programmes specific to their own field of study.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The university offers eight undergraduate and about 60 graduate programmes in English.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Since 1944, Aarhus University owned Cheminova, a chemical manufacturer which, among other controversies, has been selling methyl parathion pesticide to Brazil farmers.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] In 2009, senior researcher Mette Jensen emailed her colleagues at AU, asking whether they thought Cheminova should stop selling the controversial pesticides.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] For this, the university threatened her with dismissal.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The university's Pro-Vice-Chancellor Søren E.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Frandsen denied that the university had made any mistakes or threatened the freedom of speech and academic freedom of its staff.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] On 30 April 2015, Cheminova was sold to the FMC Corporation for DKK 8.5 billion, a controversial issue in itself.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Aarhus University is home to 15 Centres of Excellence supported by the Danish National Research Foundation and a considerable number of major research centres.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Some of the university's other major research centres include MindLab and iNANO.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] MINDLAB was established with a DKK 120 million grant awarded by the Danish Ministry of Science, Technology and Innovation.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] At MINDLab neuroscientists, psychologists, biologists, statisticians and researchers from other fields work together to understand the brain, its disorders, and its development through physical and social interactions – and vice versa.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Hence, the programme encompasses physics, chemistry, biology, molecular biology, mathematics and computer science.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] In 2011 the National Environmental Research Institute of Denmark (NERI) was organisatorically moved from the Danish Ministry of Environment and Energy and merged into AU, under the new name Danish Centre for Environment and Energy (DCE).
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] DCE consists of two departments: department of Ecoscience and Department of Environmental Sciences, as well as a common secretariat, all under the Faculty of Technical Sciences.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The core obligations of DCE continues to be to provide research based monitoring and advice to the Danish Government on environmental issues and conduct independent research and education within the same fields.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Also in 2011 the Agricultural Research Institute of the Ministry of Agriculture was merged into AU.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] First as a separate faculty for Agricultural Research, later as part of the Faculty of Technical Sciences.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The former departments are now organised as Departments of Agroecology, Animal Sciences, and Food Science, together with a common secretariat: Danish Centre for Food and Agriculture (DCA).
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The core obligations of DCA is to provide advice and supporting research to the Ministry of Agriculture and Fisheries, while the departments also engage in independent research and teaching.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The Global Rust Reference Center provides testing and investigation services of new and difficult cases of wheat stem rust/black stem rust.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Students from different fields meet in the numerous Friday bars and at various events organized by student organizations.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The Friday bars are often organised by students from the different departments who set up a small, local bar in a canteen or classroom where beers and non-alcoholic drinks are served.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The university also offers the Student bar (*Studenterbaren*) though Studenterhus Aarhus.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The university also has a number of libraries, some of which are open around the clock with student or employee cards.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Almost every department has its own library, but the main library is the State and University Library.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] It has an extensive electronic journal database which students and staff can access either at the library or from home.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Aarhus University Sports (AUS) is open to all university students and organises a wide range of activities from badminton, to fencing and chess.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The largest student organisations at Aarhus University are the Student Union (*Studenterrådet ved Aarhus Universitet*) and *Studenterlauget*.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The Student Union represents the main student body at Aarhus University in many boards and forums, while *Studenterlauget* is a mainly social organisation at School of Business and Social Sciences.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The Student Union has both student seats on the university board.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The Student Union also arranges annual concerts and seminars, and publishes the student magazine *Delfinen* (The Dolphin).
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The Conservative Students union publishes the student magazine *Critique*.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The Liberal Students union publishes the leaflet Minerva.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Aarhus University offers many activities and services for foreign and Danish students.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Several "Friday Bars", clubs organized and crewed by students at the university offer cheap beer and drinks, which has a wide appeal to the student body.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Studenternes Hus (The Students House) was built in 1964 at the central campus to accommodate students organisations, activities, festivities and gatherings.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Among many other things, the buildings are headquarters to the students organisation *Studenterhus Aarhus*, and Aarhus University offers a free membership to all exchange students.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The Students House is a meeting place for international and Danish students in Aarhus and *Studenterhus Aarhus* organize social and cultural activities throughout the year, ranging from parties and road trips, to language classes and weekly international nights (a popular dinner club).
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The Students' House including the Student bar used to be run by the independent Studenterhusfonden, but was taken over by the university itself in 2020.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] AUS is the official sports club of Aarhus University, and is open to all university students.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] It is an umbrella organisation consisting of 18 independent member clubs, which host a wide range of activities, from badminton to fencing to chess.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] In addition, AUS also offers independent activities such as indoor soccer tournaments, badminton facilities, and surfing trips.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Dale's Café is a meeting place for international students and the university's PhD students that opened in 2011.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The café offers coffee, sandwiches and a wide selection of beers.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] It has an informal lounge area where students and young researchers can relax while enjoying snacks and beverages.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Like the main building, Dale's Café is named after Aarhus University's 2010 Nobel Laureate in Economic Sciences, Dale T.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Mortensen Building houses the International Centre, the PhD House and the IC Dormitory, which contains 28 dorm rooms and two apartments dedicated to recently arrived international PhD students.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Klubben (in English 'the club') is a bar located at the former ASB (Aarhus School of Business), now under the faculty of School of Business and Social Sciences.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The bar is open during regular school hours and weekdays, but hosts larger parties during Fridays and in relation to major sports events.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Admittance is usually restricted to students of the School of Business and Social Sciences.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Studenterlauget, School of Business and Social Sciences (at the former ASB) is currently the largest student organisation in Denmark.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The organisation has approximately 4,000 members whom they service through nine smaller "business units".
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Studenterlauget has around 300 student employees.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Aarhus University is highly ranked by international organizations and maintains its own page listing its current rankings.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] It is ranked 71st by the Shanghai Ranking (2021), 89th by National Taiwan University Ranking (2018), 95th by the *U.S.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] News & World Report* (2018), 106th by *Times Higher Education World University Rankings* (2021), and 155th by *QS World University Rankings* (2021).
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Aarhus University is a member of the Coimbra Group and of the Utrecht Network.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] Aarhus university is also an active member of the University of the Arctic.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] UArctic is an international cooperative network based in the Circumpolar Arctic region, consisting of more than 200 universities, colleges, and other organizations with an interest in promoting education and research in the Arctic region.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The university participates in UArctic's mobility program north2north.
[src:citizen-science/aarhus-university] The aim of that program is to enable students of member institutions to study in different parts of the North.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] After Reddit was sold to Condé Nast Publications in 2006, Swartz became more involved in activism, helping launch the Progressive Change Campaign Committee in 2009.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] In 2010, he became a research fellow at Harvard University's Safra Research Lab on Institutional Corruption, directed by Lawrence Lessig.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] He founded the online group Demand Progress, known for its campaign against the Stop Online Piracy Act.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Federal prosecutors, led by Carmen Ortiz, charged him with two counts of wire fraud and eleven violations of the Computer Fraud and Abuse Act, carrying a cumulative maximum penalty of $1 million in fines, 35 years in prison, asset forfeiture, restitution, and supervised release.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Swartz declined a plea bargain under which he would have served six months in federal prison.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Two days after the prosecution rejected a counter-offer by Swartz, he was found dead in his Brooklyn apartment.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] In 2013, Swartz was inducted posthumously into the Internet Hall of Fame.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Aaron Hillel Swartz was born in Highland Park, 25 miles (40 kilometers) north of Chicago, to a Jewish family.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] He was the eldest child of Susan and Robert Swartz and brother to Noah and Ben Swartz.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] His father founded the software firm Mark Williams Company.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] At an early age, Swartz immersed himself in the study of computers, programming, the Internet, and Internet culture.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] He attended North Shore Country Day School, a small private school near Chicago, until ninth grade, when he left high school and enrolled in courses at Lake Forest College.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] In 1999, at age 12, he created the website The Info Network, a user-generated encyclopedia.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] The site won the ArsDigita Prize, given to young people who create "useful, educational, and collaborative" noncommercial websites, and led to early recognition of Swartz's nascent talent in coding.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] At age 14, he became a member of the working group that authored the RSS 1.0 web syndication specification.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] A year later, he became involved in the Creative Commons organization.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] In 2004, he enrolled at Stanford University but left the school after his first year.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] During Swartz's first year at Stanford, he applied to Y Combinator's first Summer Founders Program, proposing to work on a startup called Infogami, a flexible content management system designed to create rich and visually interesting websites or a form of wiki for structured data.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] After working on it with co-founder Simon Carstensen over the summer of 2005, Swartz opted not to return to Stanford, choosing instead to continue to develop and seek funding for Infogami.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] As part of his work on Infogami, Swartz created the web.py web application framework because he was unhappy with other available systems in the Python programming language.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] In the early fall of 2005, he worked with his fellow co-founders of another nascent Y Combinator firm, Reddit, to rewrite its Lisp codebase using Python and web.py.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Although Infogami's platform was abandoned after Not a Bug was acquired, Infogami's software was used to support the Internet Archive's Open Library project and the web.py web framework was used as the basis for many other projects by Swartz and many others.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] When Infogami failed to find further funding, Y Combinator organizers suggested Infogami merge with Reddit, which it did in November 2005, creating a new firm, Not a Bug, devoted to promoting both products.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] As a result, Swartz was given the title of co-founder of Reddit.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Although both projects initially struggled, Reddit made large gains in popularity in 2005–2006.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] In October 2006, based largely on Reddit's success, Not a Bug was acquired by Condé Nast Publications, owner of *Wired* magazine.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Swartz moved with his company to San Francisco to continue to work on Reddit for *Wired*.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] He found corporate office life uncongenial and in January 2007 was asked to resign from the company.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] In September 2007, he joined Infogami co-founder Simon Carstensen to launch a new firm, Jottit, in another attempt to create a Markdown-driven content management system in Python.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] In 2008, Swartz founded Watchdog.net, "the good government site with teeth", to aggregate and visualize data about politicians.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] That year, he wrote a widely circulated *Guerilla Open Access Manifesto*.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] On December 27, 2010, he filed a Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request to learn about the treatment of Chelsea Manning, alleged source for WikiLeaks.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] His activism has been praised by digital rights groups such as the Electronic Frontier Foundation (EFF).
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] In 2008, Swartz downloaded about 2.7 million federal court documents stored in the PACER (Public Access to Court Electronic Records) database managed by the Administrative Office of the United States Courts.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] The *Huffington Post* characterized his actions this way: "Swartz downloaded public court documents from the PACER system in an effort to make them available outside of the expensive service.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] PACER was charging eight cents per page for information that Carl Malamud, who founded the nonprofit group Public.Resource.Org, contended should be free, because federal documents are not covered by copyright.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] The fees were "plowed back to the courts to finance technology, but the system [ran] a budget surplus of some $150 million, according to court reports," reported *The New York Times*.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] After reading Malamud's call for action, Swartz used a Perl computer script running on Amazon cloud servers to download the documents, using credentials belonging to a Sacramento library.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] From September 4 to 20, 2008, it accessed documents and uploaded them to a cloud computing service.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] He released the documents to Malamud's organization.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] On September 29, 2008, the GPO suspended the free trial, "pending an evaluation" of the program.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Swartz's actions were subsequently investigated by the FBI.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] The case was closed after two months with no charges filed.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] At a 2013 memorial for Swartz, Malamud recalled their work with PACER.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] District Court records out from behind PACER's "pay wall", he said, and found them full of privacy violations, including medical records and the names of minor children and confidential informants.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] A more detailed account of his collaboration with Swartz on the PACER project appears in an essay on Malamud's website.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] *The New York Times* similarly reported Swartz had downloaded "an estimated 20 percent of the entire database".
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Based on the facts that Swartz downloaded 2.7 million documents while PACER, at the time, contained 500 million, Lee concluded that Swartz downloaded less than one percent of the database.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] In 2009, wanting to learn about effective activism, Swartz helped launch the Progressive Change Campaign Committee.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] In 2010, Swartz co-founded Demand Progress, a political advocacy group that organizes people online to "take action by contacting Congress and other leaders, funding pressure tactics, and spreading the word" about civil liberties, government reform, and other issues.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] During academic year 2010–11, Swartz conducted research studies on political corruption as a Lab Fellow in Harvard University's Edmond J.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Safra Research Lab on Institutional Corruption.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Now it's up to you to change the system. ...
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] After the bill's defeat, Swartz was the keynote speaker at the F2C:Freedom to Connect 2012 event in Washington, D.C., on May 21, 2012.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] He added, "We won this fight because everyone made themselves the hero of their own story.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Swartz also spoke on the topic at an event organized by ThoughtWorks.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Swartz participated in Wikipedia beginning in August 2003 under the username AaronSw.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] In 2006, he ran unsuccessfully for the Wikimedia Foundation's Board of Trustees.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Swartz came to his conclusions by counting the number of characters editors added to particular articles, while Wales counted the total number of edits.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] In January 2013, shortly after he died, WikiLeaks said that Aaron Swartz had helped WikiLeaks and talked to Julian Assange in 2010 and 2011.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] WikiLeaks also said they had "strong reasons to believe, but cannot prove" he may have been a source, possibly breaking WikiLeaks' rules about source anonymity.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] WikiLeaks may have made the statements to imply that Swartz was targeted by the US Attorney's Office and Secret Service in order to get at WikiLeaks.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] According to state and federal authorities, Swartz used JSTOR, a digital repository, to download a large number of academic journal articles through MIT's computer network over the course of a few weeks in late 2010 and early 2011.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Visitors to MIT's "open campus" were authorized to access JSTOR through its network; Swartz, as a research fellow at Harvard University, also had a JSTOR account.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] On September 25, 2010, the IP address 18.55.6.215, part of the MIT network, began sending hundreds of PDF download requests per minute to the JSTOR website, enough to slow the site's performance.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] This prompted a block of the IP address.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] In the morning, another IP address, also from within the MIT network, began sending more PDF download requests, resulting in a temporary block on the firewall level of all MIT computers in the entire 18.0.0.0/8 range.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] According to authorities, Swartz downloaded the documents through a laptop connected to a networking switch in a controlled-access wiring closet at MIT.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] The closet's door was kept unlocked, according to press reports.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] When it was discovered, a video camera was placed in the room to record Swartz; his computer was left untouched.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] The recording was stopped once Swartz was identified, but rather than pursue a civil lawsuit against him, JSTOR settled with him in June 2011; under the terms of the settlement, he surrendered the downloaded data.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] On July 30, 2013, JSTOR released 300 partially redacted documents used as incriminating evidence against Swartz, originally sent to the United States Attorney's Office in response to subpoenas in the case *United States v.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] On the night of January 6, 2011, Swartz was arrested near the Harvard campus by MIT Police and a Secret Service agent, and arraigned in Cambridge District Court on two state charges of breaking and entering with intent to commit a felony.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] On July 11, 2011, he was indicted by a federal grand jury on charges of wire fraud, computer fraud, unlawfully obtaining information from a protected computer, and recklessly damaging a protected computer.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] On November 17, 2011, Swartz was indicted by a Middlesex County Superior Court grand jury on state charges of breaking and entering with intent, grand larceny, and unauthorized access to a computer network.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] On December 16, 2011, state prosecutors filed a notice that they were dropping the two original charges, and the charges listed in the November 17, 2011, indictment were dropped on March 8, 2012.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] According to a spokesperson for the Middlesex County prosecutor, this was done to avoid impeding a federal prosecution headed by Stephen P.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Heymann, supported by evidence provided by Secret Service agent Michael S.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] On September 12, 2012, federal prosecutors filed a superseding indictment adding nine more felony counts, increasing Swartz's maximum criminal exposure to 50 years of imprisonment and $1 million in fines.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] During plea negotiations with Swartz's attorneys, the prosecutors offered to recommend a sentence of six months in a low-security prison if Swartz pled guilty to 13 federal crimes.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Swartz and his lead attorney rejected the deal, opting instead for a trial where prosecutors would be forced to justify their pursuit of him.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] The federal prosecution involved what was characterized by numerous critics (such as former Nixon White House counsel John Dean) as an "overcharging" 13-count indictment and "overzealous", "Nixonian" prosecution for alleged computer crimes, brought by then U.S.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Attorney for Massachusetts Carmen Ortiz.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Swartz died by suicide on January 11, 2013.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] After his death, federal prosecutors dropped the charges.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] On December 4, 2013, due to a Freedom of Information Act suit by the investigations editor of *Wired* magazine, several documents related to the case were released by the Secret Service, including a video of Swartz entering the MIT network closet.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Swartz was in an open relationship with Quinn Norton between 2007 and 2011 and dated Taren Stinebrickner-Kauffman from 2011 until his death in 2013, contemplating marriage with her.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] He also reportedly had same-sex relationships, and was skeptical of the idea of sexual identity.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Aside from his work, he posted frequently on Twitter, Reddit and his personal website.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] On the evening of January 11, 2013, Swartz's girlfriend, Stinebrickner-Kauffman, found him dead in his Brooklyn apartment.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] A spokesperson for New York's Medical Examiner reported that he had hanged himself.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Days before Swartz's funeral, Lawrence Lessig eulogized him in an essay, "Prosecutor as Bully".
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] He decried the disproportionality of Swartz's prosecution and said, "The question this government needs to answer is why it was so necessary that Aaron Swartz be labeled a 'felon'.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] For in the 18 months of negotiations, that was what he was not willing to accept." Cory Doctorow wrote, "Aaron had an unbeatable combination of political insight, technical skill, and intelligence about people and issues.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] I think he could have revolutionized American (and worldwide) politics.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Swartz's funeral services were held on January 15, 2013, at Central Avenue Synagogue in Highland Park, Illinois.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Tim Berners-Lee, creator of the World Wide Web, delivered a eulogy.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] He is buried at Shalom Memorial Park in Arlington Heights.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] The same day, *The Wall Street Journal* published a story based in part on an interview with Taren Stinebrickner-Kauffman.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] She told the *Journal* that Swartz lacked the money to pay for a trial and "it was too hard for him to ... make that part of his life go public" by asking for help.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] He was also distressed, she said, because two of his friends had just been subpoenaed and because he no longer believed that MIT would try to stop the prosecution.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] For donations in his memory, Swartz's family recommended GiveWell, an organization Swartz admired, had collaborated with, and made his sole beneficiary in his will.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] On January 19, hundreds attended a memorial at the Cooper Union, speakers at which included Taren Stinebrickner-Kauffman, open source advocate Doc Searls, Creative Commons' Glenn Otis Brown, journalist Quinn Norton, Roy Singham of ThoughtWorks, and David Segal of Demand Progress.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] On January 24, there was a memorial at the Internet Archive headquarters in San Francisco (video) at which Stinebrickner-Kauffman, Alex Stamos, Brewster Kahle, Peter Eckersley, and Carl Malamud spoke.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] On February 4, a memorial was held in the Cannon House Office Building on Capitol Hill; speakers included Senator Ron Wyden and Representatives Darrell Issa, Alan Grayson, and Jared Polis.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Other lawmakers in attendance included Senator Elizabeth Warren and Representatives Zoe Lofgren and Jan Schakowsky.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Harvey Silverglate was a featured speaker at a Demand Progress rally in Swartz's memory.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] A memorial also took place on March 12 at the MIT Media Lab.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] On February 2, 2025, a statue of Swartz was unveiled at the Internet Archive building in San Francisco.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] This was organized by Pablo Peniche and Lisa Rein.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] The statue stands in the building's lobby.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Attorney for the District of Massachusetts, said in a statement: "As a parent and a sister, I can only imagine the pain felt by the family and friends of Aaron Swartz, ...
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] On January 12, 2013, Swartz's family and partner issued a statement criticizing the prosecutors and MIT.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] At the time, MIT maintained an open-campus policy along with an "open network".
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Two days after Swartz's death, MIT President L.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Rafael Reif commissioned professor Hal Abelson to lead an analysis of MIT's options and decisions relating to Swartz's "legal struggles".
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] To help guide the fact-finding stage of the review, MIT created a website where community members could suggest questions and issues for the review to address.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Swartz's attorneys requested that all pretrial discovery documents be made public, a move MIT opposed.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Swartz allies have criticized MIT's opposition to releasing the evidence.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] On July 26, 2013, the Abelson panel submitted a report to Reif, who authorized its public release on July 30.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] The panel reported that MIT had not supported charges against Swartz and cleared the institution of wrongdoing, but also noted that despite MIT's advocacy for open access culture at the institutional level and beyond, the university never extended that support to Swartz.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] The report revealed, for example, that while MIT considered issuing a public statement about its position on the case, it never did so.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] As editor Hrag Vartanian writes in *Hyperallergic*, the Brooklyn muralist BAMN ("By Any Means Necessary") created a mural of Swartz.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] "Swartz was an amazing human being who fought tirelessly for our right to a free and open Internet", BAMN said.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] "He was much more than just the 'Reddit guy'." On April 17, 2013, Yuval Noah Harari called Swartz "the first martyr of the Freedom of Information movement".
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] But according to Harari, Swartz's stance did not illustrate belief in the freedom of persons or speech but stemmed from his generation's conviction that above all else, information should be free.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Swartz's legacy has reportedly strengthened the open access to scholarship movement.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] In Illinois, his home state, Swartz's influence led state university faculties to adopt policies in favor of open access.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] On January 13, 2013, members of Anonymous hacked two websites on the MIT domain, replacing them with tributes to Swartz that called on members of the Internet community to use his death as a rallying point for the open access movement.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] The banner included a list of demands for improvements in the U.S. copyright system, along with Swartz's *Guerilla Open Access Manifesto.* On the night of January 18, MIT's email system was taken offline for ten hours.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] On January 22, email sent to MIT was redirected by hackers Aush0k and TibitXimer to the Korea Advanced Institute of Science & Technology.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] All other traffic to MIT was redirected to a computer at Harvard University that was publishing a statement headed "R.I.P Aaron Swartz", with text from a 2009 post by Swartz, accompanied by a chiptune version of "The Star-Spangled Banner".
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] MIT regained full control after about seven hours.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] In the early hours of January 26, Anonymous hacked the U.S.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Sentencing Commission website, USSC.gov.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] The homepage was replaced by an embedded YouTube video, *Anonymous Operation Last Resort*.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] The video statement said Swartz "faced an impossible choice".
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] A hacker downloaded "hundreds of thousands" of scientific-journal articles from a Swiss publisher's website and republished them on the open Web in Swartz's honor a week before the first anniversary of his death.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] After Swartz's death, more than 50,000 people signed an online petition to the White House calling for Ortiz's removal "for overreach in the case of Aaron Swartz".
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] A similar petition was submitted calling for prosecutor Stephen Heymann's firing.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] In January 2015, the White House declined both petitions.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] On August 3, 2013, Swartz was posthumously inducted into the Internet Hall of Fame.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] A hackathon was held in Swartz's memory around the date of his birthday in 2013.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] On the weekend of November 8–10, 2013, inspired by Swartz's work and life, a second annual hackathon was held in at least 16 cities around the world.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Preliminary topics worked on at the 2013 Aaron Swartz Hackathon were privacy and software tools, transparency, activism, access, legal fixes, and a low-cost book scanner.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] In January 2014, Lawrence Lessig led a walk across New Hampshire in honor of Swartz, rallying for campaign finance reform.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] In 2017, the Turkish-Dutch artist Ahmet Öğüt commemorated Swartz in a work titled "Information Power to The People", which depicted his bust.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Swartz's supporters responded to news of his death with an effort called #PDFTribute to promote Open Access.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] On January 12, Eva Vivalt, a development economist at the World Bank, began posting her academic articles online using the hashtag *#pdftribute* as a tribute to Swartz.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Swartz's story has exposed the topic of open access to scientific publications to wider audiences.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Many institutions and personalities have since campaigned for open access to scientific knowledge.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Swartz's death prompted calls for more open access to scholarly data (e.g., open science data).
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] The Think Computer Foundation and the Center for Information Technology Policy (CITP) at Princeton University announced scholarships awarded in memory of Swartz.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] In 2013, Swartz was posthumously awarded the American Library Association's James Madison Award for being an "outspoken advocate for public participation in government and unrestricted access to peer-reviewed scholarly articles".
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] In March, the editor and editorial board of the *Journal of Library Administration* resigned *en masse*, citing a dispute with the journal's publisher, Routledge.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] One board member wrote of a "crisis of conscience about publishing in a journal that was not open access" after Swartz died.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] In 2002, Swartz had said that when he died, he wanted the contents of his hard drives made publicly available.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] House of Representatives—Republican Darrell Issa and Democrats Zoe Lofgren and Jared Polis—all on the House Judiciary Committee, raised questions about the government's handling of the case.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Calling the charges against him "ridiculous and trumped up", Polis called Swartz a "martyr" whose death illustrated the need for Congress to limit the discretion of federal prosecutors.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Senator Elizabeth Warren issued a statement saying that Swartz's "advocacy for Internet freedom, social justice, and Wall Street reform demonstrated ... the power of his ideas".
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] In a letter to Attorney General Eric Holder, Senator John Cornyn asked, "On what basis did the U.S.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Attorney for the District of Massachusetts conclude that her office's conduct was 'appropriate'?" and "Was the prosecution of Mr.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Issa, who chaired the House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform, announced that he would investigate the Justice Department's actions in prosecuting Swartz.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] In a statement to *The Huffington Post*, he praised Swartz's work on "open government and free access to the people".
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Issa's investigation garnered some bipartisan support.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] On January 28, 2013, Issa and ranking committee member Elijah Cummings published a letter to Holder asking why federal prosecutors had filed the superseding indictment.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] On February 20, WBUR reported that Ortiz was expected to testify at an upcoming Oversight Committee hearing about her office's handling of Swartz's case.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] On February 22, Associate Deputy Attorney General Steven Reich conducted a briefing for congressional staffers involved in the investigation.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] They were told that Swartz's *Guerilla Open Access Manifesto* played a role in prosecutorial decision-making.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Congressional staffers left this briefing believing that prosecutors thought Swartz had to be convicted of a felony carrying at least a short prison sentence in order to justify having filed charges against him.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Excoriating the Department of Justice as the "Department of Vengeance", Stinebrickner-Kauffman told the *Guardian* that the DOJ had erred in relying on Swartz's *Guerilla Open Access Manifesto* as an indication of his beliefs by 2010.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] She said, "He was no longer a single issue activist.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] He was into lots of things, from healthcare to climate change to money in politics." On March 6, Holder testified before the Senate Judiciary Committee that the case was "a good use of prosecutorial discretion".
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] In response, Stinebrickner-Kauffman issued a statement repeating and amplifying her claims of prosecutorial misconduct.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] On March 22, Senator Al Franken wrote in a letter to Holder that "charging a young man like Mr.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] In 2013, Lofgren introduced a bill, *Aaron's Law* (H.R.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] 1196), to exclude terms of service violations from the 1986 Computer Fraud and Abuse Act and from the wire fraud statute.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Lessig wrote of the bill, "this is a critically important change....
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] The CFAA was the hook for the government's bullying....
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] In a single line: no longer would it be a felony to breach a contract." Professor Orin Kerr, a specialist in the nexus between computer law and criminal law, wrote that he had been arguing for precisely this sort of reform of the Act for years.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] The ACLU also called for reform of the CFAA to "remove the dangerously broad criminalization of online activity".
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] The EFF mounted a campaign for these reforms.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Lessig's inaugural Chair lecture as Furman Professor of Law and Leadership was titled *Aaron's Laws: Law and Justice in a Digital Age*; he dedicated the lecture to Swartz.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] The Aaron's Law bill stalled in committee.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Brian Knappenberger alleges this was due to Oracle Corporation's financial interest in maintaining the status quo.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] The Fair Access to Science and Technology Research Act (FASTR) is a bill that would mandate earlier public release of taxpayer-funded research.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] FASTR has been described as "The Other Aaron's Law".
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Senators Wyden and Cornyn introduced the Senate version in 2013, 2015 and 2017, while the bill was introduced to the House of Representatives by Lofgren, Mike Doyle, and Kevin Yoder.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Wyden wrote of the bill, "the FASTR act provides that access to taxpayer funded research should never be hidden behind a paywall." The legislation did not pass, but it prompted more open access on the part of the US government.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Since 2013, Aaron Swartz Day has been celebrated on his birthday, November 8, with hackathons and livestreamed talks related to the many issues Swartz was passionate about, such as open access and progressive politics and economics.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Past speakers include Chelsea Manning, Barrett Brown, Trevor Timm of the Freedom of the Press Foundation, Cory Doctorow, Cindy Cohn, Jason Leopold, and Brewster Kahle.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Swartz has been featured in various works of art and has posthumously received dedications from numerous artists.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] He appeared in a few documentaries, including *Aardvark'd: 12 Weeks with Geeks* in 2005.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] After leaving Reddit he appeared in *Steal This Film II* (2007).
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Swartz's first posthumous work was in 2013, when Kenneth Goldsmith dedicated his "Printing out the Internet" exhibition to Swartz.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] On January 11, 2014, marking the first anniversary of his death, a preview was released of *The Internet's Own Boy: The Story of Aaron Swartz*, a documentary about Swartz, the NSA and SOPA.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] The film was officially released at the January 2014 Sundance Film Festival.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] *Democracy Now!* covered the release of the documentary, as well as Swartz's life and legal case, in a sprawling interview with director Brian Knappenberger, Swartz's father, brother, and his attorney.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] The documentary is released under a Creative Commons License; it debuted in theaters and on-demand in June 2014.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Mashable called the documentary "a powerful homage to Aaron Swartz".
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Its debut at Sundance received a standing ovation.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] In October 2014, *Killswitch*, a documentary film featuring Swartz, Lessig, Tim Wu, and Edward Snowden, premiered at the Woodstock Film Festival, where it won the award for Best Editing.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] The film focuses on Swartz's role in advocating for internet freedoms.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] In February 2015, Congressman Alan Grayson invited *Killswitch* to screen at the Capitol Visitor Center in Washington, D.C.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] The event was held on the eve of the Federal Communications Commission's historic decision on net neutrality.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] At the event, Grayson, Lessig, and Free Press CEO Craig Aaron spoke about Swartz and his fight for a free and open Internet.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Grayson called *Killswitch* "one of the most honest accounts of the battle to control the Internet—and access to information itself." Richard von Busack of the Metro Silicon Valley said *Killswitch* contains "some of the most lapidary use of found footage this side of The Atomic Café".
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Fred Swegles of the *Orange County Register* wrote, "Anyone who values unfettered access to online information is apt to be captivated by *Killswitch*, a gripping and fast-paced documentary." Kathy Gill of GeekWire wrote, "*Killswitch* is much more than a dry recitation of technical history.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Director Ali Akbarzadeh, producer Jeff Horn, and writer Chris Dollar created a human-centered story.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] He appeared in the unreleased film *War for the Web* where he had been interviewed a year prior to his death.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] The documentary was ultimately cancelled as it failed to reach its funding goal, but the footage was later used in *The Internet's Own Boy*.
[src:citizen-science/aaron-swartz] Another biographical film about Swartz, *Think Aaron*, was being developed by HBO Films as of 2020.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] The academy was founded in Nanjing, China, in 1928, and was re-established in Taiwan in 1949 following the Chinese Civil War.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] As an educational institute, it provides PhD training and scholarship through its English-language Taiwan International Graduate Program in biology, agriculture, chemistry, physics, informatics, and earth and environmental sciences.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] Membership in Academia Sinica is determined through the election of academicians.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] An academician of Academia Sinica is the highest academic honor in the country.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] The current president of the academy since 2016 is James C.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] Liao, an expert in metabolic engineering, systems biology and synthetic biology.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] Academia Sinica was established in April 1928 in the capital city of Nanking by the National Government of the Republic of China as the country's highest research organization.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] Its name is a Latin title whose literal meaning is "Chinese Academy".
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] The academy's first president was the philosopher Cai Yuanpei and its first director-general was the scholar Yang Xingfo.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] According to historian James Reardon-Anderson, it was "by far the best-funded, most prominent research organ in Republican China".
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] Prior to World War II, Academia Sinica received one-third of all government research expenditures and was also funded by the British and American Boxer Indemnities.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] The academy's early expenditures encompassed buying the lands, buildings, and equipment necessary to support a staff dedicated to the study of applied sciences.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] Under Cai's direction, Academia Sinica adopted European and American institutional models, including the practice of electing academicians.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] Cai envisioned the academy's mission as modernizing Chinese academia by "saving the nation through scholarship" and "saving the nation through science".
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] He advocated for the academic freedom of educational administration, so that the academy's scholarship could develop autonomously without interference from politics.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] Under Cai and Yang, the academy operated independently of the Kuomintang (KMT) government and attained membership in the International Council of Scientific Unions.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] By 1931, ten research institutes—ranging from physics to philology to zoology—were in operation.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] In 1935, president Ding Wenjiang established a system of academic assessors in 1935.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] During the Second Sino-Japanese War, Cai died in 1940 and was succeeded as president by geologist Chu Chia-hua, who organized the relocation of the academy's artifacts from Kunming when fighting intensified there.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] After the Surrender of Japan, the academy's headquarters returned to Nanking.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] In October 1946, president Chu Chia-hua organized the election of the academy's first group of academicians.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] They included mathematicians Su Buqing, Shiing-Shen Chern, and Hua Luogeng; chemists Hsien Wu, Zhuang Changgong, K.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] Chen, and Hou Debang; geologists Li Siguang, Weng Wenhao, Yang Zhongjian, and Zhang Hongzhao; meteorologist Chu Coching; engineer Mao Yisheng; and historian-linguists Fu Ssu-nien and Chen Yinke; among others.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] Of the 81 academicians elected, 49 were educated in the U.S., 23 in Europe, and five in Japan; six—including archaeologist Dong Zuobin and historians Gu Jiegang and Liu Yizheng—were educated domestically.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] On December 19, 1948, all of the academy's institutes unanimously voted to move to Taiwan via Guangxi and Guangdong, due to the outbreak of the Chinese Civil War.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] However, only Academia Sinica's Institute of Mathematics and the Institute of History and Philology were able to relocate to Taiwan; the remainder of the academy's property and affiliates in mainland China were absorbed into the Chinese Academy of Sciences.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] Of the original group of 81 academicians, only nine moved to Taiwan.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] The academy was low on monetary funds, and reopened with the Institute of History and Philology in December 1954.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] In the same year, its main campus was constructed in Jiuzhuang, Nangang, Taipei.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] Due to the importance of agriculture to the economy of Taiwan, efforts were made to revive the Institute of Botany.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] The second convocation of the Academia Sinica was held in 1957.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] At the same time, the mainland part of Academia Sinica remained functioning under Communist rule and was renamed as the Chinese Academy of Sciences in the 1980s.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] In the 2000s, many of the current institutes and research centers were established, partially through reorganization of old ones.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] Academia Sinica's first PhD program, the Taiwan International Graduate Program, was inaugurated in 2006.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] The president of Academia Sinica is appointed by the president of the Republic of China (Taiwan) from three candidates recommended by the Council Meeting.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] The president of Academia Sinica must be an academician.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] After the appointment, the president serves a five-year term and can serve up to two consecutive terms.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] Academia Sinica's current president is James C.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] Liao, a biochemist, who replaced Chi-Huey Wong, a biological chemist and the Parsons Foundation Professor and Chair of the Department of Chemical and Biomolecular Engineering at the University of California, Los Angeles, as the 11th president on 21 June 2016.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] Lee, won the Nobel Prize in Chemistry for "contributions to the dynamics of chemical elementary processes".
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] The Convocation of Academia Sinica consists of 281 academicians, including 105 domestic and 176 overseas appointed scientists.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] Seven academicians of Academia Sinica are Nobel laureates.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] Academician membership is an honorary lifetime privilege without remuneration.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] They do not necessarily perform research or reside at the Academia Sinica campus.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] According to their own expertise, academicians are grouped into three divisions: Mathematics and Physical Sciences, Life Sciences, and Social Sciences and Humanities.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] A maximum number of ten new members is allocated to each of the three divisions during the biennial convocation.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] The eligibility of the academicians is not restricted to the residents of Republic of China (Taiwan) citizens.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] More than half of the academicians are overseas scholars and scientists.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] At the convocation, the academicians elect new academicians and honorary academicians, and elect members to the Council of Academia Sinica.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] The convocation can also recommend policies to the government on academic research.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] The academicians also have responsibilities to carry out research at the government's request, although the government has never requested any task.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] Academicians are elected every two years, with nominations open in July and ending in October.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] Outcome of election to academicians are publicly announced in July the following year.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] Election to the academy is regarded a national honor in Taiwan.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] Up until the 34th convocation of academicians in 2022, any scientist of Chinese descent could be elected a member of Academia Sinica.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] Starting in 2023, election is to be restricted to citizens of the Republic of China.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] This change led Academia Sinica to discuss formally classifying non-Taiwanese members as honorary or foreign members.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] Such a classification system would require amendments to the Organic Act of the Academia Sinica.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] A group of academicians proposed that membership be further restricted to Taiwan passport or national identification card holders.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] Academia Sinica has its main campus located in Nangang, Taipei, and runs over 40 research stations distributed across the country and throughout the world.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] The main campus in Jiuzhuang, Nangang was constructed in 1954.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] Three physical sciences institutes, Mathematics, Astronomy, and Atomic and Molecular Sciences, are located in the main campus of National Taiwan University in Gongguan, Daan, Taipei.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] A joint office between the two institutions was established in 2014.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] A campus in the Shalun Smart Green Energy Science City, near the Tainan High Speed Rail station, Guiren District, Tainan, opened in 2024.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] The Southern Campus is part of an effort to promote regional balance in the academic landscape of Taiwan and will prioritize research on agricultural biotechnology, sustainable development, and archaeology of early Taiwanese history and culture.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] In general Academia Sinica is a non-teaching institution, but it has very close collaboration with the top research universities in Taiwan, such as National Taiwan University, National Tsing Hua University, National Yang Ming Chiao Tung University and National Central University.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] Many research fellows from Academia Sinica have a second appointment or joint professorship at these universities.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] In addition, Academia Sinica established joint PhD programs in biological sciences with Taiwan's universities, such as the Doctoral Degree Program in Marine Biotechnology with National Taiwan Ocean University.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] Through these mechanisms, the faculty at Academia Sinica give lecture courses and supervise graduate students.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] Since 2002, Academia Sinica set up the Taiwan International Graduate Program (TIGP), open to local and international students for PhD programs.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] All courses at TIGP are conducted in English.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] Students can choose their advisor among a faculty selected for the program out of outstanding researchers and professors appointed at Academia Sinica or at one of the partner universities (or both).
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] Currently, admittance to the programme guarantees a monthly stipend of 40,000 NTD, roughly $1,200 or €1,150 in their first year and up to 50,000 NTD, roughly $1,500 or €1,400 in their third year.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] The TIGP offers PhD programs only in selected disciplines agreed upon by Academia Sinica and its national research universities partners.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] The program offers doctoral degrees in highly interdisciplinary areas in the physical sciences, applied sciences, engineering, biological and agricultural sciences, health and medical sciences, humanities and social sciences.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] Academia Sinica has a high number of both domestic and international postdoctoral fellows.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] They are funded by grants of the Ministry of Science and Technology or by Academia Sinica.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] The institute has extensive cooperation with research and academic institutions from other countries (such as Harvard-Yenching Institute) and hosts several foreign institutes and their scholars.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] The Taipei Center of the French School of Asian Studies (EFEO) was hosted by the Institute of Modern History, AS, from 1992 to 1996 and since 1996 by the Institute of History and Philology.
[src:citizen-science/academia-sinica] Its research projects center on the local and cultural history of Taiwan and China, and it organizes conferences and talks, support visiting scholars and students, and hosts EFEO fellows.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] Conservative activists such as David Horowitz have argued that there is a bias against Christians and conservatives in academia.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] Barry Ames et al., John Lee and Henry Giroux have argued that these claims are based upon anecdotal evidence that would not reliably indicate systematic bias, and that the divide is due to self-selection due to conservatives simply being less likely to pursue an academic career.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] Russell Jacoby has argued that claims of academic bias have been used to push measures that infringe on academic freedom.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] One study of academic philosophers found that while half of respondents believed that ideological discrimination was wrong, a significant minority believed discrimination against individuals with opposing ideologies was justified.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] A 2017 paper argued that left-wing ideologies had taken over criminology in the 1960s and 1970s, observing a massive increase in research around fields such as radical, Marxist and feminist criminology.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] The authors also argue that even in the modern day, much of the writing in criminology remains primarily political in both origin and purpose.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] This was confirmed by the results of the study.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] Other researchers also argue that political bias manifests in scientific research, influencing how ideological groups are described, what measurements are used, the interpretation of results and which results are published.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] A 2018 study found bias amongst criminal law students, with students engaging in motivated reasoning favourable to their political in-group and demonstrating bias towards their political in-group.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] Mark Horowitz also argues that researchers' political views can bias their research.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] A 2005 paper argued that, controlling for student ability, there was no evidence of any disciplines being biased against conservative students in grading.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] In contrast, the researchers did find some disciplines, such as economics and business, where conservative students achieved higher grades than would be expected by student ability.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] Justin Tetrault argues that research into hate groups relied too much upon stereotypes rather than rigorous analysis, likely because said stereotypes appealed to researchers' own beliefs.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] It has been argued that apparent evidence of a "prejudice gap" between right-wingers and left-wingers—the idea that right-wingers are more prejudiced than left-wingers—was caused by researchers having not measured groups that left-wingers would be prejudiced towards.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] It has been suggested that this was because this was not regarded as prejudice or was not seen as worthy of investigation.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] Christine Reyna argues that ideological bias can affect how scales are constructed and interpreted in multiple ways.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] A 2019 study by the researchers measuring "actively open-minded thinking" noted that the researchers' original scale was biased against religious individuals due to test items, skewing correlations, and that the team had not realised this error for almost two decades, requiring a new scale.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] Zipp, have said that studies on the political orientations of professors are faulty, having focused on unrepresentative institutions and fields; when taken as a whole, they say that academia has become more moderate over time.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] The American Council of Trustees and Alumni, a conservative group, argues that course curriculums betray a progressive bias.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] However, John Lee argues that this research is not based on a probability sample and uses a research design that cannot rule out explanations other than political bias.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] Furthermore, research suggests little or no leftward movement among college students while they are in college.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] Academic bias has also been argued as a problem due to discrimination against conservative students.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] Research has indicated that conservative Christians may experience discrimination on colleges and universities, but these studies are anecdotal and rely on self-reported perceptions of discrimination.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] For example, the Hyers' study includes "Belief Conflicts" and "Interaction Difficulties" as discriminatory events.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] However, other work suggests that very few students experience discrimination based on political ideology.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] Phillip Gray argues that ideological bias in political science risks creating "blind spots", whereby certain ideas and assumptions are just accepted as normal and not challenged.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] Gray argues that this could mean that issues that concern the ideology of the dominant majority could receive a lot of focus, while issues that concern less prominent ideologies could be seen as less worthy of investigation and thus be consequently understudied.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] This risks resulting in a fairly ideologically homogenous field whereby certain "givens" are just accepted and thus not examined.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] In addition, Gray argues that this means that certain studies are not given adequate examination if they confirm the dominant group's ideological priors, even if the studies are flawed.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] Gray further argues that ideological bias in academia risks portraying other political groups not as another group of actors with their own beliefs but rather as a threat (too ignorant or prejudiced to know what is good) or menace (inherently inclined towards destructive acts and policies).
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] Cofnas et al. argue that activism within social science can undermine trust in scientists.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] Brandt et al. argue that bias can limit what topics are researched and thus limit scientific knowledge as a whole.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] In addition, political bias in social science can risk creating a perception amongst the general public that the scientific field is producing politically biased findings and thus not worthy of receiving public funds.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] Surveys show that a college education tends to have a "regression to the mean" effect whereby both left-wing students and right-wing students moderate their views.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] Students also become more supportive of dissent and free speech during their education.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] An early audit study published in 1986 suggested that entrance into an American clinical psychology graduate program was negatively affected by whether the applicant was a fundamentalist Christian.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] One study examined the comments made by members of an American medical school admission committee towards 21 Christian applicants.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] It concluded that applicants were more likely to be criticised when responding to a question on abortion with an anti-abortion response.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] Reber assert that an implicit bias against theism limits possible insights in the field of psychology.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] Jeff Colgan argues that, amongst international relations data, there can be interpretive biases by researchers depending on their nationality, with bias towards the United States being common due to a large number of scholars being from the US.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] Sexism in academia refers to the academic bias and discrimination by a particular sex or gender in academic institutions, particularly universities, due to the ideologies, practices, and reinforcements that privilege one sex or gender over another.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] Sexism in academia is not limited to but primarily affects women who are denied the professional achievements awarded to men in their respective fields such as positions, tenure and awards.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] A vignette study found academic discrimination against men in Germany.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] Studies have also suggested that one reason for the unwillingness of conservatives to pursue academic careers may be because conservatives prefer higher paying jobs and are not as tolerant of controversial ideas as progressives.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] Empirical support for self-selection can be found in the work of Neil Gross.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] Gross conducted an audit study whereby he sent emails to directors of graduate study programs.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] He varied the emails so that some of them indicated the student supported the presidential candidacy of Senator John McCain, some of them supported the presidential candidacy of then Senator Barack Obama and some of them were politically neutral.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] He found that the directors of graduate study programs did not significantly vary in their treatment of the senders of the letters regardless of the implied political advocacy of that sender.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] His work suggests an absence of systematic discrimination against political conservatives.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] Academic bias can refer to several types of logocentrism or phonocentrism. or the belief that some sciences and disciplines rank higher than others.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] Asle Toje argues that while academic bias does not seem to make scholars dishonest, it does affect what questions are deemed worthy of research and what conclusions are deemed career-advancing.
[src:citizen-science/academic-bias] Toje also argues that the field of social science is filled with biased terminology that *a priori* discredits certain perspectives while lending credence to others.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] While the core of academic freedom covers scholars acting in an academic capacity (as teachers or researchers expressing strictly scholarly viewpoints), an expansive interpretation extends these occupational safeguards to scholars' speech on matters outside their professional expertise.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Academic tenure protects academic freedom by ensuring that teachers can be fired only for causes such as gross professional incompetence or behavior that evokes condemnation from the academic community itself.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] The academic community pressuring scholars can reduce academic freedom.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Historically, academic freedom emerged tentatively, as academics in medieval and early modern Europe could face repression for acting in ways considered objectionable by religious authorities or by governments.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Scholars tend to link the institutionalization of academic freedom to the rise of the modern research university and the Humboldtian model of higher education from the 19th century.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] By one estimate, academic freedom has substantially increased worldwide since the 1960s.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Academic freedom is more likely in liberal democratic states, while it is more heavily constrained in authoritarian states, illiberal states, and states embroiled in military conflict.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Since 2013, while some countries have seen improvements to academic freedom, the overall trend is towards reductions in freedom.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] A minimal definition of academic freedom is that a teacher has a right to instruct, and a student has a right to learn in an academic setting unhampered by interference.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Other definitions include the right of teachers to engage in social and political criticism.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] A broader definition of academic freedom incorporates individual, extramural and institutional components.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Under this broader definition, an academic has freedom of expression without government interference, but this freedom is circumscribed by academic expertise and position.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Academic freedom of speech is therefore narrower than a general freedom of speech.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] For example, a non-academic has the freedom of speech to criticize the efficacy of vaccines, but only has *academic freedom* to do so if they possess the prerequisite academic qualifications to do so.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Unlike public speech, academic speech is also subject to quality controls by academic peers, for example through peer review.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Norwegian education sees it as a guarantee that research and teaching is "intellectually and morally independent of all political and economic interests", leading to openness, free enquiry and debate.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] The laissez-faire approach of unaccountable academic freedom is contrasted with democratic accountability of academia.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Historically, academic freedom emerged tentatively.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] In 1155, the Holy Roman Emperor Frederick I Barbarossa issued the document *Authentica habita* which laid out rights and privileges of students and scholars, which included immunity from civil jurisdiction and freedom of movement for the purposes of studying and teaching.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Similarly, civil disturbances, such as the St Scholastica Day riot of 1355 at the University of Oxford often led to great autonomy for universities.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] And even those scholars who committed theological heresy, such as John Wyclif and Jan Hus, has support due to their roles as faculty at a university.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] The Humboldtian model of higher education from the 19th century enshrined the basic ideas of academic freedom and diffused them to other countries.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Wilhelm von Humboldt was a philosopher and linguist who was given the authority to create a new university in Berlin in the early 19th century.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] In founding the Humboldt University of Berlin he created a university that adhered to two principles of academic freedom: freedom of scientific inquiry and the unity between research and teaching.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] According to Humboldt, the fundamental proposition underlying the principles of academic freedom was to uphold the view that science is not something that has already been found but as knowledge that will never be fully discovered and, yet, needs to be searched for unceasingly.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] The university he founded later became a model and inspiration for modern colleges in Germany and universities in the West.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] During this period there was also a sense that universities must be insulated from the pressures of donors, boards of trustees and state governments.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] One notable instance was the case of the resignation of Brown University president Elisha Andrews, who advocated silver coinage to reduce the impact on Americans and farmers who owed larger and larger loans due to deflation.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] The board of Brown University, many of whom were creditors and landowners and benefited from deflation, told Andrews to cease his public advocacy.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] The dean of Yale Law School, Francis Wayland, argued that Andrews' free expression threatened donations to Brown, and that money was the life blood of universities.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] In 1897, Andrews was forced to offer his resignation, but there was a backlash by faculty and students who advocated that he should be protected under the principles of free speech.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] The board reversed its decision and refused Andrews' resignation.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] The concept of academic freedom was also formulated in response to the encroachments of the totalitarian state on science and academia in general for the furtherance of its own goals.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] For instance, in the Soviet Union, scientific research was brought under strict political control in the 1930s.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] A number of research areas were declared "bourgeois pseudoscience" and forbidden, notably genetics (see "Lysenkoism") and sociology.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Marxist scientist John Desmond Bernal characterized this as part of the interdependence between "applied science" and "pure science".
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Michael Polanyi argued that a structure of liberty is essential for the advancement of science.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] In 1936, as a consequence of an invitation to give lectures for the Ministry of Heavy Industry in the USSR, Polanyi met Bukharin, who told him that in socialist societies all scientific research is directed to accord with the needs of the latest five-year plan.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Demands in Britain for centrally planned scientific research led Polanyi, together with John Baker, to found the Society for Freedom in Science.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] The society promoted a liberal conception of science as free enquiry against the instrumental view that science should exist primarily to serve the needs of society.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] In a series of articles, re-published in *The Contempt of Freedom* (1940) and *The Logic of Liberty* (1951), Polanyi claimed that co-operation among scientists is analogous to the way in which agents co-ordinate themselves within a free market.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Just as consumers in a free market determine the value of products, science is a spontaneous order that arises as a consequence of open debate among specialists.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Proponents of academic freedom believe that the freedom of inquiry by students and faculty members is essential to the mission of the academy.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] They argue that academic communities are repeatedly targeted for repression due to their ability to shape and control the flow of information.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] When scholars attempt to teach or communicate ideas or facts that are inconvenient to external political groups or to authorities, they may find themselves targeted for public vilification, job loss, imprisonment, or even death.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] For example, in North Africa, a professor of public health discovered that his country's infant mortality rate was higher than government figures indicated.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] The fate of biology in the Soviet Union is cited by Jasper Becker as a reason why society has an interest in protecting academic freedom.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Lysenko called this "Michurinism", but it is more commonly known today as Lysenkoism, and named after him.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Lysenko's ideas appealed to the Soviet leadership, in part because of their value as propaganda, and he was ultimately made director of the Soviet Academy of Agricultural Sciences.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Subsequently, Lysenko directed a purge of scientists who professed "harmful ideas", resulting in the expulsion, imprisonment, or death of hundreds of Soviet scientists.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Lysenko's ideas were then implemented on collectivized farms in the Soviet Union and China.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Famines that resulted partly from Lysenko's influence are believed to have killed 30 million people in China alone during the Great Leap Forward.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Sociologist Ruth Pearce argued that the concept of academic freedom exists to protect scholarship from censure by state or religious authorities or others, and not to defend intolerance.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Academic freedom can be reduced through scholars pressuring other scholars and resulting self-censorship or political bias.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] A large-scale empirical study, covering more than 157 countries over the 1900-2015 period, links academic freedom to the quality and quantity of patents filed in a given country.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] David Audretsch and colleagues estimate that academic freedom has declined over the last decade for the first time over their century-long observation period, resulting in at least 4% fewer patents filed.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] The study claims to be the first to link academic freedom to economic growth through an innovation channel.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Academic freedom has also been identified as a leading indicator for whether a government will become more or less democratic.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] In 2020, the V-Dem Institute partnered with Scholars at Risk to create the first index of Academic freedom.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] The index provides retroactive ratings for countries going back to 1900 that are also updated yearly.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] As of 2025, academic freedom overall around the world has been in retreat since 2013.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Causes cited have included authoritarianism as well as political polarization and populism.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] The concept of academic freedom as a right of faculty members is an established part of most legal systems.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] While in the United States the constitutional protection of academic freedom derives from the guarantee of free speech under the First Amendment, the constitutions of other countries (particularly in civil law systems) typically grant a separate right to free learning, teaching, and research.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Concerns have been expressed by Freedom House and others about protections for freedom of speech and academic freedom at Australia's universities.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] In 2018, the Australian Government asked former Chief Justice Robert French to conduct an independent review of freedom of speech and academic freedom in Australian higher education.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] While French disagreed that there was a "freedom of speech crisis" on campuses, he nonetheless noted the risks to freedom posed by the various and vaguely-worded protections then in place.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Concerns include the influence of the People's Republic of China on university administrations; 'deplatforming' of controversial speakers and viewpoints; and demands that academics refrain from contesting one another's conclusions.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] During the late 1950s and early 1960s, students and faculty began advocating for the democratization of university life in Chile.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] However, after the 1973 coup, academic freedom under the Pinochet military dictatorship was repressed.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Nevertheless, during the 1980s, students and faculty, with support from members of the public, collaborated to protect academic freedom.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Since the transition to democracy after the end of the Pinochet regime in 1990, academic freedom in higher education in Chile has been strong.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] In 2025, Chile ranked in the top ten percent of countries on the Academic Freedom Index (AFI).
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Academic freedom is severely limited in China.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Academics have noted an incentive not to express 'incorrect' opinions about issues sensitive to the Government of China and the ruling Chinese Communist Party (CCP).
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] These efforts have been effective in causing academics to self-censor and shift academic discourse.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] During the general secretaryship of Xi Jinping, universities in the country have increasingly been put under the direct management of a CCP committee secretary and have intensified ideological controls.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] In December 2020, the Associated Press reported that China was controlling scientific research into the origins of COVID-19 under direct orders from CCP general secretary Xi Jinping.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] According to the report, an order by China's State Council required all research to be approved by a task force under their management, saying scientific publication should be orchestrated like "a game of chess", warning that those who publish without permission will be held accountable.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] According to National Public Radio, from 2013 to 2017, at least 109 universities in China issued their first charters affirming the CCP leadership.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] In 2020, Shanghai's Fudan University removed freedom of thought from its charter following the December 2019 revision of the school charter to emphasize loyalty to the CCP.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Hong Kong academia expressed concerns about the impact of the 2020 Hong Kong National Security Law on academic freedom in Hong Kong.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] As of 2025, it ranked in the bottom 20% worldwide for academic freedom according to the Academic Freedom Index.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] In an August 2021 study, Jue Jiang from the University of London argued that academic freedom in China is impaired by the CCP's system of student informants, who are recruited and encouraged to watch and inform on their professors on university campuses.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Danish law guarantees both institutional and individual academic freedom at universities, yet the country ranked 24th of 28 EU states in 2017 and 32nd of 179 countries in a 2024 study.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Researchers and the academic union DM reported in 2024 that political pressure, insecure employment, competition for external funding and limited public awareness are weakening independence and discouraging basic research.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] In 2021, a political campaign against alleged “pseudo-research and activism” led to parliamentary resolution V137, with some politicians demanding interventions, lists of “dangerous” programmes and the closure of certain research fields.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Over 3,000 academics signed a petition arguing the resolution threatened academic freedom and could increase self-censorship and harassment, including on social media.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Earlier and ongoing controversies include the 1986 government-ordered closure of a sociology programme at Copenhagen University and recent proposals from Danish People's Party and Liberal Alliance to shut down Roskilde University for ideological reasons, including for being 'woke'.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Central European University was forced to leave Hungary after its academic freedom deteriorated under Victor Orban.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] In 2020, students protested the overhauling by the government of the University of Theater and Film Arts.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] As of 2025, India ranks in the bottom 10-20% of countries globally.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Protections for academic freedom for research, teaching and other activity "to question and test received wisdom, to put forward new ideas and to state controversial or unpopular opinions" without being disadvantaged, are provided in Section 14 of the 1997 Universities Act.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Academic freedom in Israel is taken from "the Law of the Council for Higher Education".
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Paragraph 15 in which it states that "a recognized institution is free to all its academic and administrative matters, within the framework of its budget, as it sees fit.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] It seems that the paragraph is worded in a clear and comprehensible way even for laymen.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] The body that is supposed to guard academic freedom, as well as maintain an adequate academic level in the higher education institutions, is the Council for Higher Education – hereinafter "The Council".
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] This council consists of academics who serve as professors at universities, and public figures, with the Minister of Education as the head of the council.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] At the disposal of "The Council" is an executive body called the "Committee for Planning and Budgeting", which mainly deals with the matter of universities budgeting and establishing relevant procedures and guidelines for budget and salary matters.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Another body that is supposed to guard academic freedom is the "Committee of the Heads of the Universities", which is a voluntary body, but has an influence on the work of the Legislature and "The Council ".
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Through their employee committees, and through the personal activity of each of them, these bodies can try and influence the preservation of academic freedom.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] In general, it can be said that the essential academic freedom, the one aimed at the freedom of teaching and research, was preserved, and the government neither interfered nor tried to interfere in these contents.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Its way of influencing this matter is by providing incentives for teaching in this or that way, or for research in certain fields, and this is through grants.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] The fact that the government finances a significant percentage of the current budget of the universities (around 70% or more), also allows the government to decide what will be the tuition fee for a student at the budgeted universities in Israel.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] But, In 2021, an academic committee of the prestigious Israel Prize decided to award the Israel Prize in the field of mathematics and computer science to Professor Oded Goldreich from the Weizmann Institute of Science.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] The award committee appealed to the Supreme Court for a violation of its academic freedom, and the court overturned the decision, and ordered the Minister of Education to award Goldreich the award.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Godreich received the award a year later.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] In recent years, a fierce debate has erupted on the issue of academic freedom, following extreme political statements by a number of university faculty members.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] The vast majority of the controversial statements were those that called for an academic boycott of Israel, or support for organizations that support an economic and academic boycott of Israel.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] All the more, is it permissible for the professor to express a political position during his teaching, and even to invite representatives of political bodies to lecture in his classes, and without maintaining a balance between those invited.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Referring to that background, the Minister of Education at the time Naftali Bennett (in 2017) asked Prof.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Asa Kasher to compile an academic Code of Ethics for universities, a code that was approved by "The Council" in March 2018.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] All the research universities (7 universities), with the exception of Ben-Gurion University of the Negev, which already had for an academic code of ethics that also included the issue of freedom of expression, refused to adopt this code on the grounds of infringing academic freedom.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] All research universities in Israel have a Chief internal auditor, relatively independent.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] In the Chapter II Constitution of Mauritius, academics have the right to: the protection of freedom of conscience, protection of freedom of expression, protection of freedom of assembly and association, protection of freedom to establish schools and the protection from discrimination.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] The institutional bureaucracy and the dependence on the state for funds has restricted the freedom of academics to criticize government policy.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Academic freedom became a public issue in May 2009 when the university spoke out against the vice chancellor Professor I.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Fagoonee, who had forwarded a circular sent by the Ministry of Education to academics.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] This circular targeted public officers and required them to consult their superiors before speaking to the press.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] The pushback resulted in the vice chancellor stepping down, with the author speculating the government used the vice chancellor as the scapegoat for its unpopular proposal to try to curtail academic freedom.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] In the Netherlands the academic freedom is limited relative to other Western European countries.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] In November 1985 the Dutch Ministry of Education published a policy paper titled *Higher Education: Autonomy and Quality*.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] This paper had a proposal that steered away from traditional education and informed that the future of higher education sector should not be regulated by the central government.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] In 1992 the Law of Higher Education and Research (Wet op het hoger onderwijs en wetenschappelijk onderzoek, article 1.6) was published and became effective in 1993.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] However, this law governs only certain institutions.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Academic freedom is protected by the 1987 Philippine Constitution, which states in Article XIV, Section 5 (2), "Academic freedom shall be enjoyed in all institutions of higher learning".
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Republic Act 8292 (Higher Education Modernization Act of 1997) states that "all institutions of higher learning, public or private, shall enjoy academic freedom and institutional autonomy".
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Implementing rules for this law state that "all SUCs shall enjoy academic freedom and institutional autonomy".
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Academic freedom is also enshrined in Republic Act 9500 (The University of the Philippines Charter of 2008), which states, "the national university has the right and responsibility to exercise academic freedom".
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Threats to academic freedom include attempts to establish a military presence in campuses or corporations dictating that a school teach only "marketable courses".
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Other threats may come in the form of state-sponsored historical distortion and the red-tagging, surveillance, and harassment of students and faculty.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] In Freedom House's 2025 Academic Freedom Index, the Philippines scored 0.624 (out of 1, 1 is best), the country's lowest score in nearly 40 years.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] According to the FAU Academic Freedom Index, in 2025 South Africa scored a 0.83 on a scale of 0 to 1, which has been pretty constant between 2015 to 2025.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Section 16(1) of the Constitution of the Republic of South Africa, established in 1996, guarantees everyone the right to freedom of expression, including “academic freedom and freedom of scientific research".
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Under apartheid, universities were racially segregated, a legacy that influences the lives of students and academics in South Africa today.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] The Population Registration Act of 1950 classified South Africans by race, using categories of White, Indian, Coloured, and Black.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Based on this legislation, the Extension of University Education Act 45 dictated that students of nonwhite descent were not permitted to register at traditionally white universities unless given expression permission by the minister.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] As a result, several non-white universities were established, including the University of Durban-Westville for Indians, and the University of the Western Cape at Belleville, open to the Coloured community.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Fort Hare University, University of Zululand, and the University of the North at Turfloop were established or reformed as institutions for specific ethnic groups.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] The higher education system remained starkly segregated until 1988, when the National Party government, led by F.W. de Klerk, put forth a set of policies repealing various systematic segregationist laws.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] As of 2007, there have been scandals over the restricted academic freedom at a number of universities in South Africa.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] The University of KwaZulu-Natal received fame over its restricted academic freedom and the scandal that occurred in 2007.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Fazel Khan was fired in April 2007 for "bringing the university into disrepute" after releasing information to the news media about being airbrushed from a photograph in a campus publication because of his participation in a staff strike.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] The South African Council on Higher Education released a report stating that the state is influencing academic freedom.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Public universities are more susceptible to political pressure because they receive funds from the public.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Among postdoctoral fellows, there exist sentiments of being taken advantage of, based on the personal testimonies of postdoctoral fellows at the University of Johannesburg.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] While these conversations occur in many postdoctoral settings, much of the conversation arises from South Africa, where fellows report that the unstable nature of postdoctoral contracts is lends itself to insufficient compensation disproportionate to the demand for fellows.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Multiple accounts and reports from postdoctoral fellows have shown two conflicting ideas: one believing the postdoc system to be a reliable pathway for a future scholarly career and one perceiving the system as unreliable and exploitive.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Institutional capture and patronage networks, informal institutions intertwined with South Africa's academic landscape, Jonas Magedi argues, compromises the integrity of higher education.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Specifically, pressure from external sources may suppress dissent and inhibit further growth, especially in the area of humanities.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] In 2016, Erdogan was given the power to appoint professors by decree.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] This, along with firings, harassment and imprisonment of academics helped to drop Turkey to one of the countries with the lowest academic freedom in the world by 2021, leading to protests at institutions like Boğaziçi University.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] The Robbins Report on Higher Education, commissioned by the British government and published in 1963, devoted a full chapter, Chapter XVI, to Academic freedom and its scope.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] This gives a detailed discussion of the importance attached both to freedom of individual academics and of the institution itself.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] In a world, both then and now, where illiberal governments are all too ready to attack freedom of expression, the Robbins committee saw the (then) statutory protection given to academic freedom as giving some protection for society as a whole from any temptation to mount such attacks.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] When Margaret Thatcher's government sought to remove many of the statutory protections of academic freedom which Robbins had regarded as so important, she was partly frustrated by a hostile amendment to her bill in the House of Lords.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] These principles of academic freedom are thus articulated in the statutes of most UK universities.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Professor Kathleen Stock formerly of University of Sussex resigned from her role due to controversy from students and the media regarding her transphobic views.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] In response to such concerns, the Equality and Human Rights Commission has issued guidance.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] The Guidance provides detailed procedures for universities to consider in determining whether or not specific events can go ahead.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] It also provides ways to reduce any potential barriers for freedom of speech in regards to specific events.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] The guidance also makes clear the statutory requirement of universities to ensure they protect freedom of speech on campus however as well as compliance with the Prevent Strategy and the Equality Act 2010.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Academic freedom started in America after the Civil War disrupted the previously stagnating systems of higher education.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] The educational system that Germany had was analyzed by universities to progress fields of research.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Johns Hopkins University was the first to use this education system.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Prior to the turn of the twentieth century, a professor by the name of Edward Ross published the free silver movement supporting document known as *Honest Dollars.* The document placed the professor in political disagreement with the founders of Stanford University.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] The Stanford family made their money from the railroad industry that the professor had publicly ridiculed.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] In 1900, the professor expressed politically charged statements that called for the expulsion of Japanese immigrants from the country which would lead to his termination from the university.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] This decision was followed by seven other professors resigning from the university and elevated the matter to national scrutiny.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] This event would set in motion the creation of the AAUP to provide monetary and legal security, filling the gaps in many of their contracts.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] The principle also refers to the ability of teachers, students, and educational institutions to pursue knowledge without unreasonable political or government interference.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] The Principles have only the character of private pronouncements, not that of binding law.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] In short the statement argues that professors have the privilege to search for truth and knowledge and the right to impart those truths and knowledge to others, including students, the academy, and the general public, unfettered by political or ideological pressure.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Since being drafted, this definition has undergone two revisions in 1970 and 1999 respectively.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] The 1970 revision declares that the protections of academic freedom "apply not only to the full-time probationary and the tenured teacher, but also to all others, such as part-time faculty and teaching assistants, who exercise teaching responsibilities".
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] The 1999 revision places emphasis on the idea that post-tenure review should be conducted in a manner that respects academic freedom and due process.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Supreme Court began to take up the matter starting with the case of *Sweezy v.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Board of Regents* (1967), the Supreme Court made connections between the First Amendment and academic freedom as an especially important protection on the grounds that it was crucial to everyone.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Such First Amendment protections only applied to public institutions, and academic freedom contains protections outside of the First Amendment as the Court never outright declared that it contained academic freedom.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Some accreditors work with American colleges and universities, including private and religious institutions, to support academic freedom in various forms, although this varies by accreditor.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Additionally, the AAUP, which is not an accrediting body, works with these same institutions.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] The AAUP does not always agree with the accrediting bodies on the standards of protection of academic freedom and tenure.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] The AAUP censures those colleges and universities which it has found, after its own investigations, to violate these principles.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] By 2022, 88 percent of four-year colleges and universities will limit student free speech, reversing a 15-year trend, according to the College Speech Codes annual report.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] The Foundation for Individual Rights and Expression (FIRE) reported that 426 out of 486 institutions have at least one policy restricting student speech.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] A prominent feature of the English university concept is the freedom to appoint faculty, set standards and admit students.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] This ideal may be better described as institutional autonomy and is distinct from whatever freedom is granted to students and faculty by the institution.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] In a 2008 case, a federal court in Virginia ruled that professors have no academic freedom; *all* academic freedom resides with the university or college.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Virginia State University*, a district court judge held "that no constitutional right to academic freedom exists that would prohibit senior (university) officials from changing a grade given by (a professor) to one of his students." The court relied on mandatory precedent of the U.S.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] New Hampshire* and a case from the fourth circuit court of appeals.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] The *Stronach* court also relied on persuasive cases from several circuits of the courts of appeals, including the first, third, and seventh circuits.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] That court distinguished the situation when a university attempts to coerce a professor into changing a grade, which is clearly in violation of the First Amendment, from when university officials may, in their discretionary authority, change the grade upon appeal by a student.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] The *Stronach* case has gotten significant attention in the academic community as an important precedent.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Academic freedom and free speech rights are not coextensive, although this widely accepted view has been challenged by an "institutionalist" perspective on the First Amendment.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Academic freedom involves more than speech rights; for example, it includes the right to determine what is taught in the classroom.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] The AAUP gives teachers a set of guidelines to follow when their ideas are considered threatening to religious, political, or social agendas.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] In practice, academic freedom is protected by institutional rules and regulations, letters of appointment, faculty handbooks, collective bargaining agreements, and academic custom.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] In the U.S., the freedom of speech is guaranteed by the First Amendment, which states that "Congress shall make no law... abridging the freedom of speech, or of the press...." By extension, the First Amendment applies to all governmental institutions, including public universities.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Supreme Court has historically held that academic freedom is a First Amendment right at *public* institutions.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] However, the United States' First Amendment has generally been held to **not** apply to *private* institutions, including religious institutions.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] These private institutions may honor freedom of speech and academic freedom at their discretion.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Academic freedom is also associated with a movement to introduce intelligent design as an alternative explanation to evolution in US public schools.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Critics of the movement claim intelligent design is religiously motivated pseudoscience and cannot be allowed into the curriculum of US public schools due to the First Amendment to the United States Constitution, often citing *Kitzmiller v.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Dover Area School District* as legal precedent.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] They also reject the allegations of discrimination against proponents of intelligent design, of which investigation showed no evidence.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] A number of "academic freedom bills" have been introduced in state legislatures in the United States between 2004 and 2008.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] The bills were based largely upon language drafted by the Discovery Institute, the hub of the Intelligent Design movement, and derive from language originally drafted for the Santorum Amendment in the United States Senate.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] According to *The Wall Street Journal*, the common goal of these bills is to expose more students to articles and videos that undercut evolution, most of which are produced by advocates of intelligent design or biblical creationism.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] The American Association of University Professors has reaffirmed its opposition to these bills, including any portrayal of creationism as a scientifically credible alternative and any misrepresentation of evolution as scientifically controversial.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] As of 2013, only the Louisiana bill has been successfully passed into law.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] In 2014, a debate was held by the Academic Leadership Fellows Program (ALFP), addressing the potential need to either further revise the text, overhaul it completely, or leave it as is.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] The counterargument to revision/overhaul asserts that the AAUP's statement has aged well, and that overhauling the standard that has existed for decades would only stir up further confusion.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Instead, it is necessary to "clearly articulate the statements' intended meaning through education, discussion, and by not supporting inappropriate behavior in the name of academic freedom".
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] This debate took place in front of a live audience, who after hearing both arguments agreed overwhelmingly with keeping the statement as-is.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] In the 20th century and particularly the 1950s during McCarthyism, there was much public date in print on Communism's role in academic freedom, e.g., Sidney Hook's *Heresy, Yes–Conspiracy, No* and Whittaker Chambers' "Is Academic Freedom in Danger?" among many other books and articles.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] While some controversies of academic freedom are reflected in proposed laws that would affect large numbers of students through entire regions, many cases involve individual academics that express unpopular opinions or share politically unfavorable information.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] These individual cases may receive widespread attention and periodically test the limits of, and support for, academic freedom.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Several of these specific cases are also the foundations for later legislation.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] In 1929, Experimental Psychology professor Max Friedrich Meyer and sociology assistant professor Harmon O.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] The university was subsequently censured by the American Association of University Professors in an early case regarding academic freedom due a tenured professor.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] In 2006, Lawrence Summers, while president of Harvard University, led a discussion that was intended to identify the reasons why fewer women chose to study science and mathematics at advanced levels.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] He suggested that the possibility of intrinsic gender differences in terms of talent for science and mathematics should be explored.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] He became the target of considerable public backlash.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] His critics were, in turn, accused of attempting to suppress academic freedom.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Due to the adverse reception to his comments, he resigned after a five-year tenure.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Another significant factor of his resignation was several votes of no-confidence placed by the deans of schools, notably multiple professors in the Faculty of Arts and Sciences.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] In 2009 Thio Li-ann withdrew from an appointment at New York University School of Law after controversy erupted about some anti-gay remarks she had made, prompting a discussion of academic freedom within the law school.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Subsequently, Li-ann was asked to step down from her position in the NYU Law School.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] In 2009 the University of California at Santa Barbara accused William I.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Robinson of antisemitism after he circulated an email to his class containing photographs and paragraphs of the Holocaust juxtaposed to those of the Gaza Strip.
[src:citizen-science/academic-freedom] Robinson was fired from the university, but later the accusations were dropped after a worldwide campaign against the management of the university.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] An **active galactic nucleus** (**AGN**) is a compact region at the center of a galaxy that emits a significant amount of energy across the electromagnetic spectrum, with characteristics indicating that this luminosity is not produced by the stars.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] Such excess, non-stellar emissions have been observed in the radio, microwave, infrared, optical, ultra-violet, X-ray, and gamma ray wavebands.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] A galaxy hosting an AGN is called an **active galaxy**.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] The non-stellar radiation from an AGN is theorized to result from the accretion of matter by a supermassive black hole at the center of its host galaxy.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] The super massive black hole at the center of the Milky Way galaxy is not currently active but it is believed to have been active about 8 billion years ago.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] Active galactic nuclei are the most luminous persistent sources of electromagnetic radiation in the universe and, as such, can be used as a means of discovering distant objects; their evolution as a function of cosmic time also puts constraints on models of the cosmos.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] The observed characteristics of an AGN depend on several properties such as the mass of the central black hole, the rate of gas accretion onto the black hole, the orientation of the accretion disk, the degree of obscuration of the nucleus by dust, and presence or absence of jets.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] Numerous subclasses of AGN have been defined on the basis of their observed characteristics; the most powerful AGN are classified as quasars.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] A blazar is an AGN with a jet pointed toward the Earth, in which radiation from the jet is enhanced by relativistic beaming.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] During the first half of the 20th century, photographic observations of nearby galaxies detected some characteristic signatures of active galactic nucleus emission, although there was not yet a physical understanding of the nature of the AGN phenomenon.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] Some early observations included the first spectroscopic detection of emission lines from the nuclei of NGC 1068 and Messier 81 by Edward Fath (published in 1909), and the discovery of the jet in Messier 87 by Heber Curtis (published in 1918).
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] Further spectroscopic studies by astronomers including Vesto Slipher, Milton Humason, and Nicholas Mayall noted the presence of unusual emission lines in some galaxy nuclei.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] In 1943, Carl Seyfert published a paper in which he described observations of nearby galaxies having bright nuclei that were sources of unusually broad emission lines.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] Galaxies observed as part of this study included NGC 1068, NGC 4151, NGC 3516, and NGC 7469.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] Active galaxies such as these are known as Seyfert galaxies in honor of Seyfert's pioneering work.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] The development of radio astronomy was a major catalyst to understanding AGN.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] Some of the earliest detected radio sources are nearby active elliptical galaxies such as Messier 87 and Centaurus A.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] Another radio source, Cygnus A, was identified by Walter Baade and Rudolph Minkowski as a tidally distorted galaxy with an unusual emission-line spectrum, having a recessional velocity of 16,700 kilometers per second.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] The 3C radio survey led to further progress in discovery of new radio sources as well as identifying the visible-light sources associated with the radio emission.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] In photographic images, some of these objects were nearly point-like or quasi-stellar in appearance, and were classified as quasi-stellar radio sources (later abbreviated as "quasars").
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] Soviet-Armenian astrophysicist Viktor Ambartsumian introduced the concept of active galactic nuclei in the early 1950s.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] At the Solvay Conference on Physics in 1958 Ambartsumian presented a report arguing that "explosions in galactic nuclei cause large amounts of mass to be expelled.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] For these explosions to occur, galactic nuclei must contain bodies of huge mass and unknown nature.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] From this point forward active galactic nuclei (AGN) became a key component in theories of galactic evolution." His idea was initially received skeptically.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] A major breakthrough was the measurement of the redshift of the quasar 3C 273 by Maarten Schmidt, published in 1963.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] Schmidt noted that if this object was extragalactic (outside the Milky Way, at a cosmological distance) then its large redshift of 0.158 implied that it was the nuclear region of a galaxy about 100 times more powerful than other radio galaxies that had been identified.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] Shortly afterward, optical spectra were used to measure the redshifts of a growing number of quasars including 3C 48, even more distant at redshift 0.37.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] The enormous luminosities of these quasars as well as their unusual spectral properties indicated that their power source could not be ordinary stars.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] Accretion of gas onto a supermassive black hole was suggested as the source of quasars' power in papers by Edwin Salpeter and Yakov Zeldovich in 1964.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] In 1969 Donald Lynden-Bell proposed that nearby galaxies contain supermassive black holes at their centers as relics of "dead" quasars, and that black hole accretion was the power source for the non-stellar emission in nearby Seyfert galaxies.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] In the 1960s and 1970s, early X-ray astronomy observations demonstrated that Seyfert galaxies and quasars are powerful sources of X-ray emission, which originates from the inner regions of black hole accretion disks.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] Today, AGN are a major topic of astrophysical research, both observational and theoretical.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] Since the late 1960s it has been argued that an AGN must be powered by accretion of mass onto massive black holes (106 to 1010 times the Solar mass).
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] AGN are both compact and persistently extremely luminous.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] Accretion can potentially give very efficient conversion of potential and kinetic energy to radiation, and a massive black hole has a high Eddington luminosity.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] As a result, it can provide the observed high persistent luminosity.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] Supermassive black holes are now believed to exist in the centres of most if not all massive galaxies, since the mass of the black hole correlates well with the velocity dispersion of the galactic bulge (the M–sigma relation) or with bulge luminosity.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] Thus, AGN-like characteristics are expected whenever a supply of material for accretion comes within the sphere of influence of the central black hole.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] In the standard model of AGN, cold material close to a black hole forms an accretion disc.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] Dissipative processes in the accretion disc transport matter inwards and angular momentum outwards, while causing the accretion disc to heat up.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] The expected spectrum of an accretion disc peaks in the optical-ultraviolet waveband; in addition, a corona of hot material forms above the accretion disc and can inverse-Compton scatter photons up to X-ray energies.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] The radiation from the accretion disc excites cold atomic material close to the black hole and this in turn radiates at particular emission lines.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] A large fraction of the AGN's radiation may be obscured by interstellar gas and dust close to the accretion disc, but (in a steady-state situation) this will be re-radiated at some other waveband, most likely the infrared.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] Some accretion discs produce jets of twin, highly collimated, and fast outflows that emerge in opposite directions from close to the disc.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] The direction of the jet ejection is determined either by the angular momentum axis of the accretion disc or the spin axis of the black hole.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] The jet production mechanism and indeed the jet composition on very small scales are not understood at present due to the resolution of astronomical instruments being too low.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] The jets have their most obvious observational effects in the radio waveband, where very-long-baseline interferometry can be used to study the synchrotron radiation they emit at resolutions of sub-parsec scales.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] However, they radiate in all wavebands from the radio through to the gamma-ray range via the synchrotron and the inverse-Compton scattering process, and so AGN jets are a second potential source of any observed continuum radiation.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] There exists a class of "radiatively inefficient" solutions to the equations that govern accretion.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] Several theories exist, but the most widely known of these is the Advection Dominated Accretion Flow (ADAF).
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] In this type of accretion, which is important for accretion rates well below the Eddington limit, the accreting matter does not form a thin disc and consequently does not efficiently radiate away the energy that it acquired as it moved close to the black hole.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] Radiatively inefficient accretion has been used to explain the lack of strong AGN-type radiation from massive black holes at the centres of elliptical galaxies in clusters, where otherwise we might expect high accretion rates and correspondingly high luminosities.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] Radiatively inefficient AGN would be expected to lack many of the characteristic features of standard AGN with an accretion disc.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] AGN are a candidate source of high and ultra-high energy cosmic rays *(see also Centrifugal mechanism of acceleration)*.
[src:citizen-science/active-galactic-nucleus] The observed AGNs are grouped into dozens of different sometimes overlapping classes.
